{"title_page": "2016 NFL season", "text_new": "{{about|the American football season in the United States|the Gaelic football season in Ireland|2016 National Football League (Ireland)}}\n{{short description|97th season in the history of the National Football League}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox NFL\n| year           = 2016\n| regular_season = {{Start date|2016|09|08}} \u2013 {{end date|2017|01|01}}\n| playoffs_start = January 7, 2017\n| NFLchampion    =[[2016 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]]\n| NFCchampion    =[[2016 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]]\n| AFCchampion    =[[2016 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]]\n| sb_name        = LI\n| sb_date        = February 5, 2017\n| sb_site        = [[NRG Stadium]], [[Houston]]\n| pb_date        = January 29, 2017\n| pb_site        = [[Camping World Stadium]], [[Orlando, Florida]]\n}}\nThe '''2016 NFL season''' was the 97th season in the history of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). The season began on September 8, 2016, with the defending [[Super Bowl 50]] champion [[2016 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]] defeating the [[2016 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]] 21\u201320 in the [[NFL Kickoff Game]] in a rematch of the Super Bowl. The season concluded with [[Super Bowl LI]], the league's championship game on February 5, 2017, at [[NRG Stadium]] in [[Houston]] with the New England Patriots defeating the Atlanta Falcons 34\u201328 in overtime.\n\nFor the first time since the [[Houston Oilers]] relocated to [[Tennessee Titans|Tennessee]] in {{nfly|1997}},<ref group=note>The Oilers received approval to relocate to [[Nashville, Tennessee]] in 1997, but elected to play at [[Liberty Bowl Memorial Stadium]] in [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]] for one season while the Nashville venue now known as [[Nissan Stadium]] was under construction.</ref> an NFL team relocated to another state, as the former [[St. Louis Rams]] moved out of [[St. Louis|St. Louis, Missouri]] and returned to [[Los Angeles]], its home from 1946 to 1994.<ref name=\"RamsMoveToLA2016\">{{cite web|last=Hanzus|first=Dan|title=Rams to relocate to L.A.; Chargers first option to join|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000621645/article/rams-to-relocate-to-la-chargers-first-option-to-join|website=NFL.com|publisher=National Football League|date=January 12, 2016|accessdate=January 13, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114055828/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000621645/article/rams-to-relocate-to-la-chargers-first-option-to-join|archivedate=January 14, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rams to Return to Los Angeles|url=http://www.stlouisrams.com/news-and-events/article-1/Rams-to-Return-to-Los-Angeles/802b4e16-671e-4864-97b6-943115cdc4cf|publisher=St. Louis Rams|date=January 12, 2016|accessdate=January 13, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113032719/http://www.stlouisrams.com/news-and-events/article-1/Rams-to-Return-to-Los-Angeles/802b4e16-671e-4864-97b6-943115cdc4cf|archivedate=January 13, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> For the first time since the [[2003 NFL season]], neither of the previous season's Super Bowl participants made the playoffs.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ortega|first=Mark E.|title=Broncos, Panthers miss playoffs after Super Bowl 50|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000763687/article/broncos-panthers-miss-playoffs-after-super-bowl-50|website=NFL.com|publisher=National Football League|date=December 26, 2016|accessdate=January 8, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170109114218/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000763687/article/broncos-panthers-miss-playoffs-after-super-bowl-50|archivedate=January 9, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe 2016 season also was the last season for the [[San Diego Chargers]] after playing in San Diego for fifty-six years before their return to the city of Los Angeles for 2017, where the franchise was based in for their first season in [[1960 Los Angeles Chargers season|1960]].\n\nThis was also the first season without any players drafted in the 1990s, as quarterback [[Peyton Manning]] and cornerback [[Charles Woodson]], both from the [[1998 NFL Draft|1998 Draft]], retired earlier in the offseason. There was still one player who had been playing since the 1990s in kicker [[Adam Vinatieri]] of the [[Indianapolis Colts]], who began his career with the Patriots in [[1996 NFL season|1996]], however, he was an undrafted free agent.\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Player movements and retirements==\nThe 2016 NFL league year began on March 9, 2016 at 4:00&nbsp;p.m. ET. On March 7 clubs started to contact and enter into contract negotiations with the certified agents of players who became unrestricted free agents upon the expiration of their [[2015 NFL season|2015]] contracts two days later. On March 9, clubs exercised options for 2016 on players who have option clauses in their 2015 contracts, submitted qualifying offers to their restricted free agents with expiring contracts and to whom desire to retain a Right of Refusal/Compensation, submitted a Minimum Salary Tender to retain exclusive negotiating rights to their players with expiring 2015 contracts and who have fewer than three accrued season of free agent credit, and teams were required to be under the salary cap, using the \"Top-51\" definition (in which the 51 highest-paid players on the team's payroll must have a collective salary cap hit below the actual cap). All 2015 players contracts expired and trading period for 2016 begin.\n\n===Free agency===\nA total of 496 players were eligible for some form of free agency at the beginning of the free agency period.<ref>{{cite web|title=Free Agency Signing Period Begins; 496 Players Become Free Agents|url=https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/Free-Agency-Signing-Period-Begins;-496-Players-Became-Free-Agents.aspx|website=nflcommunications.com|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC.|accessdate=March 9, 2016|date=March 9, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160323115626/https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/Free-Agency-Signing-Period-Begins;-496-Players-Became-Free-Agents.aspx|archivedate=March 23, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In addition, a number of highly paid players were released after the start of the league year to allow their teams to regain space under the salary cap. Among the notable players who changed teams via free agency were:\n\n*Quarterbacks [[Robert Griffin III]] (Washington to Cleveland) and [[Brock Osweiler]] (Denver to Houston)\n*Running backs [[Matt Forte]] (Chicago to New York Jets), [[Chris Ivory]] (New York Jets to Jacksonville) [[Lamar Miller]] (Miami to Houston), and [[Alfred Morris (American football)|Alfred Morris]] (Washington to Dallas)\n*Wide receivers [[Travis Benjamin]] (Cleveland to San Diego), [[Marvin Jones (wide receiver)|Marvin Jones]] (Cincinnati to Detroit), [[Rishard Matthews]] (Miami to Tennessee), and [[Mohamed Sanu]] (Cincinnati to Atlanta)\n*Tight ends [[Coby Fleener]] (Indianapolis to New Orleans) and [[Benjamin Watson]] (New Orleans to Baltimore)\n*Offensive linemen [[Alex Boone]] (San Francisco to Minnesota), [[Alex Mack]] (Cleveland to Atlanta), [[Russell Okung]] (Seattle to Denver), [[Kelechi Osemele]] (Baltimore to Oakland), [[Mitchell Schwartz]] (Cleveland to Kansas City), [[Donald Stephenson]] (Kansas City to Denver), \n*Defensive linemen [[Damon Harrison]] (New York Jets to New York Giants) [[Malik Jackson (defensive end)|Malik Jackson]] (Denver to Jacksonville), [[Brandon Mebane]] (Seattle to San Diego), and [[Olivier Vernon]] (Miami to New York Giants) \n*Linebackers [[Demario Davis]] (New York Jets to Cleveland), [[Bruce Irvin (American football)|Bruce Irvin]] (Seattle to Oakland), and [[Danny Trevathan]] (Denver to Chicago)\n*Defensive backs [[Prince Amukamara]] (New York Giants to Jacksonville), [[Tashaun Gipson]] (Cleveland to Jacksonville), [[Casey Hayward]]  (Green Bay to San Diego), [[Janoris Jenkins]] (Los Angeles to New York Giants), [[Rodney McLeod]] (Los Angeles to Philadelphia), [[Josh Norman (cornerback)|Josh Norman]] (Carolina to Washington), [[Sean Smith (cornerback)|Sean Smith]] (Kansas City to Oakland), and [[Eric Weddle]] (San Diego to Baltimore)\n\n===Trades===\n* March 9: [[2016 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia]] traded CB [[Byron Maxwell]], LB [[Kiko Alonso]], and a [[Laremy Tunsil|2016 first round pick]] to [[2016 Miami Dolphins season|Miami]] in exchange for a [[Jack Conklin|2016 first round draft pick]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Walker|first=James|title=Dolphins complete trade for Byron Maxwell, Kiko Alonso|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/14936999/miami-dolphins-complete-trade-byron-maxwell-kiko-alonso|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=March 10, 2016|date=March 10, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829025251/http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/14936999/miami-dolphins-complete-trade-byron-maxwell-kiko-alonso|archivedate=August 29, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* March 9: [[2016 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia]] traded RB [[DeMarco Murray]] along with a [[Nick Kwiatkoski|2016 fourth round pick]] to the [[2016 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee]] in exchange for a [[Connor Cook|2016 fourth round pick]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Titans to acquire RB DeMarco Murray from Eagles|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000642098/article/titans-to-acquire-rb-demarco-murray-from-eagles|website=NFL.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308072520/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000642098/article/titans-to-acquire-rb-demarco-murray-from-eagles|archivedate=March 8, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* March 11: [[2016 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia]] traded QB [[Mark Sanchez]] to the [[2016 Denver Broncos season|Denver]] in exchange for a conditional 2017 seventh-round draft pick.<ref>{{cite web|first=Marc|last=Sessler|title=Mark Sanchez acquired by Broncos in trade with Eagles|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000643643/article/broncos-trade-for-eagles-qb-mark-sanchez|publisher=NFL.com|date=March 11, 2016|accessdate=March 11, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311233409/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000643643/article/broncos-trade-for-eagles-qb-mark-sanchez|archivedate=March 11, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* March 15: [[2016 New England Patriots season|New England]] traded DE [[Chandler Jones]] to [[2016 Arizona Cardinals season|Arizona]] in exchange for G [[Jonathan Cooper]] and a [[Vonn Bell|2016 second round pick]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Patriots trade Chandler Jones to Cardinals|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000644613/article/patriots-trade-chandler-jones-to-the-cardinals|website=NFL.com|first=Marc|last=Sessler|date=March 15, 2016|accessdate=March 15, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316181247/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000644613/article/patriots-trade-chandler-jones-to-the-cardinals|archivedate=March 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* March 16: [[2016 Chicago Bears season|Chicago]] traded TE [[Martellus Bennett]] along with a 2016 sixth round pick to [[2016 New England Patriots season|New England]] in exchange for a [[Deiondre' Hall|2016 fourth round pick]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Martellus Bennett traded by Bears to Patriots|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000645101/article/martellus-bennett-traded-by-bears-to-patriots|website=NFL.com|first=Dan|last=Hanzus|date=March 16, 2016|accessdate=March 17, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160318171246/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000645101/article/martellus-bennett-traded-by-bears-to-patriots|archivedate=March 18, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* April 9: [[2016 Denver Broncos season|Denver]] traded OT [[Ryan Clady]] and a 2016 seventh round pick to the [[2016 New York Jets season|New York Jets]] in exchange for a [[LeShaun Sims|2016 fifth round pick]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Jets acquire Ryan Clady in trade with Broncos|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000651782/article/jets-acquire-ryan-clady-in-trade-with-broncos|work=NFL.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160410072046/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000651782/article/jets-acquire-ryan-clady-in-trade-with-broncos|archivedate=April 10, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n*August 16: [[2016 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee]] traded WR [[Dorial Green-Beckham]] to [[2016 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia]] in exchange for G [[Dennis Kelly (American football)|Dennis Kelly]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000685910/article/eagles-acquire-dorial-greenbeckham-from-titans|title=Eagles acquire Dorial Green-Beckham from Titans|access-date=2016-08-16|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817013206/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000685910/article/eagles-acquire-dorial-greenbeckham-from-titans|archivedate=August 17, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* September 3: [[2016 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia]] traded QB [[Sam Bradford]] to [[2016 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota]] for a [[Derek Barnett|2017 first round pick]] and conditional 2018 fourth round pick.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000694979/article/sam-bradford-traded-to-vikings-for-two-draft-picks|title=Sam Bradford traded to Vikings for two draft picks|last=Orr|first=Connor|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222003508/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000694979/article/sam-bradford-traded-to-vikings-for-two-draft-picks|archivedate=February 22, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* October 31: the [[2016 New England Patriots season|New England]] traded LB [[Jamie Collins (American football)|Jamie Collins, Sr.]] to [[2016 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland]] for a [[Trey Hendrickson|conditional 2017 third round pick]].\n\n===Notable retirements===\n<!-- General criteria for this list:  At least four Pro Bowl and/or All-Pro selections -->\n* DE [[Jared Allen]] \u2013 Five time Pro Bowler and four-time first-team AP All Pro.  Allen played for the [[Kansas City Chiefs]], [[Minnesota Vikings]], [[Chicago Bears]], and [[Carolina Panthers]] during his 12-year career. \n* RB [[Arian Foster]] \u2013 Four-time Pro Bowler and three-time AP All Pro (two first-team, one second-team).  Foster played for the [[Houston Texans]] and [[Miami Dolphins]] during his eight-year career.<ref>{{cite web |author=Wesseling, Chris |title=Dolphins' Arian Foster announces his NFL retirement |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000727497/article/dolphins-arian-foster-announces-his-nfl-retirement |work=NFL.com |date=October 25, 2016 |accessdate=October 25, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025013533/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000727497/article/dolphins-arian-foster-announces-his-nfl-retirement |archivedate=October 25, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* RB [[Marshawn Lynch]] \u2013 Five-time Pro Bowler, two time AP All Pro (one first-team, one second-team), and [[Super Bowl XLVIII]] champion.  Lynch played for the [[Buffalo Bills]] and [[Seattle Seahawks]] during his nine-year career.  Prior to the {{nfly|2017}} season, Lynch came out of retirement, signing with the [[Las Vegas Raiders|Oakland Raiders]]. \n* WR [[Calvin Johnson]] \u2013 Six-time Pro Bowler and four-time AP All Pro (three first-team, one second-team).  Johnson played his entire nine-year career for the [[Detroit Lions]].\n* QB [[Peyton Manning]] \u2013 14-time Pro Bowler, 10-time AP All Pro (seven first-team, 3 second-team), five-time [[National Football League Most Valuable Player Award|NFL MVP]], two-time [[Associated Press NFL Offensive Player of the Year Award|Offensive Player of the Year]], two-time Super Bowl champion ([[Super Bowl XLI|XLI]] and [[Super Bowl 50|50]]), and Super Bowl XLI [[Super Bowl Most Valuable Player Award|MVP]]. Manning played for the [[Indianapolis Colts]] and [[Denver Broncos]] during his 18 year career.\n* S [[Charles Woodson]] \u2013 Nine-time Pro Bowler, eight-time AP All Pro (four 1st-team, four 2nd-team), and {{nfly|2009}} [[National Football League Defensive Player of the Year Award|Defensive Player of the Year]].  Woodson shares the record for most career defensive touchdowns, with 13. He played for the [[Las Vegas Raiders|Oakland Raiders]] and [[Green Bay Packers]] during his 18-year career.\n\n===Draft===\n{{Details|2016 NFL Draft}}\nThe 2016 NFL Draft was held between April 28&nbsp;\u2212 April 30, 2016 in [[Chicago]]. By way of a trade with the [[Tennessee Titans]], the [[Los Angeles Rams]] held the [[List of first overall National Football League draft picks|first overall pick]] and selected [[Quarterback|QB]] [[Jared Goff]].\n\n==Rule changes==\nThe following rule changes were approved for the 2016 NFL season at the owners' meeting on March 22:<ref>{{cite web|last=Brinson|first=Will|title=Chop blocks hit the chopping block as NFL makes seven new rules changes|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/eye-on-football/25526663/here-are-the-seven-nfl-playing-rule-changes-for-2016|website=[[CBSSports.com]]|accessdate=March 22, 2016|date=March 22, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160323175956/http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/eye-on-football/25526663/here-are-the-seven-nfl-playing-rule-changes-for-2016|archivedate=March 23, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n* Allowing the offensive and defensive play callers on the coaching staffs to use the coach-to-player communication system regardless of whether they are on the field or in the coaches' booth.\n* Permanently adopting the extra-point rules enacted in the [[2015 NFL season]]. Extra point kicks will be from the 15 yard line, and defenses can return blocked PAT's, fumbles or interceptions on two-point tries for a two-point defensive conversion.\n* Outlaw all chop blocks anywhere on the field. Previously, the chop block was legal when an offensive lineman chops a defensive player \"while the defensive player is physically engaged above the waist by the blocking attempt of another offensive teammate\".\n* Expand the definition of a \"[[horse-collar tackle]]\" to include tackles where a player is grabbed by the jersey at or above the name plate and dragged to the ground.\n* Making the act of calling time-out when not permitted to do so subject to a delay-of-game penalty (5 yards).\n* Changing from a five-yard penalty to a loss of down when a receiver goes out of bounds and comes back in to illegally touch a forward pass.\n* Eliminating multiple spots of enforcement for a double foul committed after a change of possession.\n* The umpire will now line up in the offensive backfield directly across from the referee at all times in the game, ending the practice of the umpire moving behind the defensive line when the offense is inside the five-yard line or in the final 2:00 of the first half & the final 5:00 of the second half.\n\nThe following changes were approved for only the 2016 NFL season at the owners' meeting on March 23.  Both are subject to become permanent rules or scrapped for the 2017.\n* Moving the [[touchback]] spot after kickoffs and other free kicks to the 25-yard line, similar to the NCAA rule adopted in the [[2012 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2012 season]] (a touchback after a turnover or punt will still be placed on the 20-yard line). The goal for this rule change is to decrease the number of kickoff returns: kick returners may be more reluctant to bring the ball out from the end zone because of the greater risk of being tackled before reaching the 25-yard line. NFL officials concede that this may in fact increase kickoff returns because kickers may instead attempt to pin returners inside the 10-yard line.<ref>{{cite web|last=Breech|first=John|title=NFL implements huge new touchback rule, admits it could backfire|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/eye-on-football/25528216/nfl-implements-huge-new-touchback-rule-admits-it-could-backfire|website=[[CBSSports.com]]|accessdate=March 23, 2016|date=March 23, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160326124530/http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/eye-on-football/25528216/nfl-implements-huge-new-touchback-rule-admits-it-could-backfire|archivedate=March 26, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* Players committing two [[unsportsmanlike conduct]] penalties in the same game will be automatically ejected from the game.  This was in response to [[New York Giants]] wide receiver [[Odell Beckham Jr.]] committing three personal fouls in one game against the [[Carolina Panthers]] cornerback [[Josh Norman (cornerback)|Josh Norman]] without being ejected. This change is being referred to as the \"Odell Beckham Rule\". NFL officials, however, concede that this new rule would not have ejected Beckham since he committed personal fouls and not unsportsmanlike conduct penalties.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vacchiano|first=Ralph|title=NFL owners approve 'Odell Beckham Rule,' players will be tossed after two \u2018unsportsmanlike conduct\u2019 penalties|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/football/giants/nfl-owners-approve-odell-beckham-rule-article-1.2574788|accessdate=March 24, 2016|work=[[New York Daily News]]|date=March 24, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160326112947/http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/football/giants/nfl-owners-approve-odell-beckham-rule-article-1.2574788|archivedate=March 26, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe following changes to instant replay rules were approved for the 2016 NFL season at the owners' meeting on May 24:<ref>{{cite news|last=Orr|first=Connor|title=Changes to league's instant replay rules pass|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000664581/article/changes-to-leagues-instant-replay-system-pass|accessdate=May 24, 2016|work=[[NFL.com]]|publisher=NFL|date=May 24, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160525051653/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000664581/article/changes-to-leagues-instant-replay-system-pass|archivedate=May 25, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n*Refining what is a reviewable play, including the following:\n**Plays involving possession.\n**Plays involving touching of either the ball or the ground.\n**Plays governed by the goal line.\n**Plays governed by the boundary lines.\n**Plays governed by the line of scrimmage.\n**Plays governed by the line to gain (1st down).\n**Number of players on the field at the snap.\n**Game administration (which includes correct application of the playing rules, proper down, spot of the foul for penalty application, and game clock status (running clock, not running clock, end of period)\n\nAdditional rule updates made for the 2016 season include:\n*Banning players from wearing hoodies under their uniform shirts.  This was adopted in response to [[Green Bay Packers]] wide receiver [[James Jones (wide receiver)|James Jones]] using that style in the 2015 season, which hid his name plate under the hood.<ref name=\"Source: Player hoodies banned on field as part of NFL rules updates\">{{cite web|last=Seifert|first=Kevin|title=Source: Player hoodies banned on field as part of NFL rules updates|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/16057096/player-hoodies-banned-assistant-coaches-barred-field-part-nfl-rule-updates|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=June 9, 2016|date=June 9, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829013216/http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/16057096/player-hoodies-banned-assistant-coaches-barred-field-part-nfl-rule-updates|archivedate=August 29, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n*Banning any coaches except for the head coach from entering the field of play, and then only to check on an injured player.  This was in response to the incident involving [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] assistant coach [[Joey Porter]] and several [[Cincinnati Bengals]] players, especially [[Adam Jones (American football)|Adam Jones]], during the [[2015\u201316 NFL playoffs]].<ref name=\"Source: Player hoodies banned on field as part of NFL rules updates\" />\n*If the coin does not flip (as it did during the 2015\u201316 NFL Playoff game between the Green Bay Packers and the [[Arizona Cardinals]]), during the pre-game or pre-OT toss, the Referee can re-toss the coin using the captain's original call.\n*Practice squads can now have up to four players with two seasons of experience, an increase from the two players allowed the previous two years.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Aaron|title=NFL changes rules for practice-squad members|url=https://www.chron.com/sports/texans/article/NFL-changes-rules-for-practice-squad-members-8318574.php|accessdate=June 22, 2016|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=June 22, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160622175508/http://www.chron.com/sports/texans/article/NFL-changes-rules-for-practice-squad-members-8318574.php|archivedate=June 22, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n*Injury reports will no longer include the \"probable\" designation. The league had discouraged using the designation for anything beyond minor injuries after 2005 (in a game in which [[Michael Vick]], listed as probable on the injury report, also was listed as inactive), to the point where almost all of the players who were being listed as probable ultimately played. The \"questionable\" category will now be broadened to include any injury that could possibly prevent a player from entering the game, while the \"doubtful\" category will likewise be generalized to include any player who is more likely to not play than play. Prior to 2016, each designation represented the approximate odds of the player seeing any playing time: 75 percent for probable, 50 percent for questionable and 25 percent for doubtful.<ref>{{cite web|last=Florio|first=Mike|authorlink=Mike Florio|title=NFL drops \"probable\" from injury report, redefines \"questionable\" and \"doubtful\"|url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2016/08/21/nfl-drops-probable-from-injury-report-redefines-questionable-and-doubtful/|website=[[Profootballtalk.com]]|publisher=[[NBC Sports]]|accessdate=August 21, 2016|date=August 21, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822055333/http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2016/08/21/nfl-drops-probable-from-injury-report-redefines-questionable-and-doubtful/|archivedate=August 22, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==2016 deaths==\nThe following people associated with the NFL (or [[American Football League|AFL]]) died in 2016.<ref name=PFR_2016_deaths>{{cite web|title=2016 Pro Football Deaths|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2016/deaths.htm|website=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|date=June 29, 2016|accessdate=June 29, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160722164014/http://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2016/deaths.htm|archivedate=July 22, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n;Dennis Green\n[[Dennis Green]] died July 21. Green was named the head coach of the [[Minnesota Vikings]] in 1992, becoming the second full-time black head coach in NFL history ([[Art Shell]], who had been hired for the [[History of the Los Angeles Raiders|Los Angeles Raiders]] three years prior, was the first). Green spent ten years coaching the Vikings, eight of them being playoff seasons, but never made it to the Super Bowl. He then took over the [[Arizona Cardinals]] from 2004 to 2006, to much less success, most infamously in the [[2006 Chicago Bears\u2013Arizona Cardinals game|Monday Night Meltdown]], in which he let off a tirade after losing a game. Green had also spent time as an assistant coach with the [[San Francisco 49ers]] and as a broadcast commentator. Green was 67.<ref name=NYTobit>{{cite news|last1=Mather|first1=Victor|title=Dennis Green, Pioneering Coach of the Vikings and the Cardinals, Dies at 67|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/23/sports/football/dennis-green-dead.html?_r=0|accessdate=July 23, 2016|work=The New York Times|date=July 22, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727235849/http://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/23/sports/football/dennis-green-dead.html?_r=0|archivedate=July 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n;Buddy Ryan\n[[File:Buddy Ryan in 2011.jpg|thumb|Buddy Ryan]]\n[[Buddy Ryan|James \"Buddy\" Ryan]] died June 28. Ryan, a head coach and defensive coordinator who served with six NFL teams over the course of his career, was credited with inventing the [[46 defense]]. His contributions to the game were considered crucial to helping the [[New York Jets]] secure an upset win in [[Super Bowl III]] and played a key role in the [[Chicago Bears]]' rout in [[Super Bowl XX]]. His sons, [[Rex Ryan|Rex]] and [[Rob Ryan|Rob]], were both coaches with the [[Buffalo Bills]] at the time (a team the elder Ryan turned down a coaching offer from in the early years of his career). Ryan was 85.<ref>{{cite news|last=Finley|first=Patrick|title=Former Bears defensive guru Buddy Ryan dead at 85|url=http://chicago.suntimes.com/1985-chicago-bears/report-former-bears-defensive-guru-buddy-ryan-dead-at-82/|accessdate=June 28, 2016|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|date=June 28, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629234944/http://chicago.suntimes.com/1985-chicago-bears/report-former-bears-defensive-guru-buddy-ryan-dead-at-82/|archivedate=June 29, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Eckel|first=Mark|title=Former Eagles head coach Buddy Ryan was one of a kind|url=http://www.nj.com/eagles/index.ssf/2016/06/former_eagles_head_coach_buddy_ryan_was_one_of_a_k.html|accessdate=June 29, 2016|work=[[The Hunterdon County Democrat]]|date=June 28, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629161901/http://www.nj.com/eagles/index.ssf/2016/06/former_eagles_head_coach_buddy_ryan_was_one_of_a_k.html|archivedate=June 29, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n;Other notable deaths\n\n<!--ALPHABETIZED BY LAST NAME-->[[Julius Adams]], [[Caesar Belser]], [[John Binotto]], [[Cary Blanchard]], [[Ron Brace]], [[Clarence Brooks]], [[Fred Bruney]], [[Rudy Bukich]], [[Dennis Byrd]], [[Patrick Cain]], [[Keion Carpenter]], [[Gail Cogdill]], [[Bruce DeHaven]], [[David Douglas (offensive lineman)|David Douglas]], [[Robert Eddins]], [[Kimbo Slice|Kevin \"Kimbo Slice\" Ferguson]], [[Bill Glassford]], [[Ken Gorgal]], [[Quentin Groves]], [[Bob Harrison (American football)|Bob Harrison]], [[Joe Hergert]], [[Winston Hill]], [[Greg Horton]], [[Gary Jeter]], [[Paul Jetton]], [[Curley Johnson]], [[Ted Karras, Sr.|Ted Karras]], [[Johnny Lattner]], [[Jacky Lee]], [[Mike McCoy (cornerback)|Mike McCoy]], [[Joe McKnight]], [[Ted Marchibroda]], [[Andy Maurer]], [[Lou Michaels]], [[Lawrence Phillips]], [[Chuck Pitcock]], [[Fred Quillan]], [[Konrad Reuland]], [[Willie Richardson]], [[Bill Robinson (American football)|Bill Robinson]], [[Bryan Robinson (American football, born 1974)|Bryan Robinson]], [[Leo Rucka]], [[Rashaan Salaam]], [[Will Smith (defensive end)|Will Smith]], [[Bill Stanfill]], [[Steve Thompson (defensive tackle, born 1965)|Steve Thompson]], [[Zurlon Tipton]], [[Kevin Turner (running back)|Kevin Turner]], [[Bill Wade]], [[Fulton Walker]], [[Tray Walker]], [[Elmer Wingate]], [[Al Wistert]], [[John Wittenborn]], [[George Yarno]].\n\n==Regular season==\nThe 2016 [[NFL regular season|regular season]] featured 256 games which were played out over a seventeen-week schedule beginning on Thursday, September 8, 2016. Each of the league's 32 teams played a 16-game schedule, with one [[Bye (sports)|bye week]] for each team scheduled between weeks 4\u201313. The slate also featured games on [[Monday Night Football|Monday night]]. There were games played on Thursday, including the [[National Football League Kickoff game]] in [[prime time]] on September 8 and games on [[NFL on Thanksgiving Day|Thanksgiving Day]]. The regular season concluded with a full slate of 16 games on Sunday, January 1, 2017, all of which were intra-divisional matchups, as it has been since {{nfly|2010}}.\n\n;Scheduling formula\nUnder the NFL's current [[NFL scheduling formula|scheduling formula]], each team played each of the other three teams in its own division twice. In addition, a team played against all four teams in one other division from each conference. The final two games on a team's schedule were against the two teams in the team's own conference in the two divisions the team was not set to play which finished the previous season in the same rank in their division (e.g. the team which finished first in its division the previous season played each other team in its conference that also finished first in its respective division). The pre-set division pairings for 2016 were:\n{| border=0 style=\"margin: 0 0 0 1.5em;\"\n|- valign=\"top\" \n| \n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;'''Intra-conference'''<br/>\n[[AFC North]] vs. [[AFC East]]<br/>\n[[AFC South]] vs. [[AFC West]]<br/>\n[[NFC North]] vs. [[NFC East]]<br/>\n[[NFC South]] vs. [[NFC West]]<br/>\n| style=\"padding-left:40px;\" |\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;'''Inter-conference'''<br/>\n[[AFC East]] vs. [[NFC West]]<br/>\n[[AFC North]] vs. [[NFC East]]<br/>\n[[AFC South]] vs. [[NFC North]]<br/>\n[[AFC West]] vs. [[NFC South]]<br/>\n|}\n\nThe complete 2016 schedule was released on April 14, 2016. Highlights of the 2016 schedule included:\n*'''[[NFL Kickoff Game]]''': The 2016 season began with the Kickoff Game on September 8. The 2015 champion [[2016 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]] hosted the [[2016 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]] in a rematch of [[Super Bowl 50]], marking the first time since the Kickoff game was established that it was a rematch of the previous Super Bowl, and the first such meeting of both Super Bowl participants during the first week of the next season since the [[1970 NFL Season|1970 season]] (when the Minnesota Vikings and Kansas City Chiefs held a rematch of [[Super Bowl IV]] to kick off the new post-merger era). The Broncos debuted [[Trevor Siemian]] as their new starting quarterback; Siemian had been the Broncos' third-string quarterback and ascended to the starting position after [[Peyton Manning]], their starting quarterback for the 2012 through 2015 seasons, retired following Super Bowl 50, and second-stringer [[Brock Osweiler]] left as a free agent for the [[Houston Texans]].\n*'''[[NFL International Series|International Series]]''': Four games were played internationally this season. Three of the games were played in London, England and the fourth was played in [[Mexico City]], [[Mexico]]. The [[2016 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]] played host to the [[2016 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]] on October 2 at [[Wembley Stadium]], marking the fourth of at least eight consecutive years in which the Jaguars hosted a game in London. On October 23, in the first NFL game at [[Twickenham Stadium]] also in London, the [[2016 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]] hosted the [[2016 New York Giants season|New York Giants]].  The [[2016 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]] played host to the [[2016 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]] on October 30 at Wembley Stadium in London.<ref>{{cite web|title=2016 UK International Series schedule announced|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000587776/article/2016-uk-international-series-schedule-announced|publisher=NFL.com|date=November 25, 2015|accessdate=December 30, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151229001728/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000587776/article/2016-uk-international-series-schedule-announced|archivedate=December 29, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Finally, on Monday, November 21, the [[2016 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]] hosted the [[2016 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]] at [[Estadio Azteca]] in Mexico City, in the first ''[[Monday Night Football|Monday night]]'' game to be played outside of the United States and the second regular-season contest to be held in Mexico (the first being the 2005 [[F\u00fatbol Americano]] contest.)<ref>{{cite web|title=Back to Mexico: Texans-Raiders to play Nov. 21 in Mexico City|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000632878/article/back-to-mexico-texansraiders-to-play-nov-21-in-mexico-city|work=NFL.com|date=February 5, 2016|accessdate=February 5, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160206083946/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000632878/article/back-to-mexico-texansraiders-to-play-nov-21-in-mexico-city|archivedate=February 6, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n*'''[[NFL on Thanksgiving Day|Thanksgiving Day games]]''': As has been the case since 2006, three games were played on Thursday, November 24, 2016.  The [[2016 Detroit Lions season|Detroit Lions]] hosted the [[2016 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]], the [[2016 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]] hosted the [[2016 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]], and the evening game, the first Thanksgiving game to feature teams from the [[American Football Conference|AFC]] since 2013, featured the [[2016 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]] hosting the [[2016 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]].\n*'''[[National Football League Christmas games|Christmas games]]''': Christmas Day, December 25, fell on a Sunday in 2016. The Sunday afternoon games were moved to Saturday, [[Christmas Eve]], and joined by a ''[[Thursday Night Football|Thursday Night Special]]'' game between the [[2016 Cincinnati Bengals season|Bengals]] at the [[2016 Houston Texans season|Texans]]. Two nationally-televised games were played on Christmas Day; a late-afternoon ''Thursday Night Special'' game was played between the [[2016 Baltimore Ravens season|Ravens]] and [[2016 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Steelers]], while ''Sunday Night Football'' was played between the [[2016 Denver Broncos season|Broncos]] and [[2016 Kansas City Chiefs season|Chiefs]].\n\n===In-season scheduling changes===\n*'''[[Pro Football Hall of Fame Game]]''': The 2016 edition of the preseason Hall of Fame Game, between the [[2016 Green Bay Packers season|Packers]] and the [[2016 Indianapolis Colts season|Colts]], was canceled due to unsafe playing conditions at [[Tom Benson Hall of Fame Stadium]] in [[Canton, Ohio]], caused by the use of improper paints applied to the field to create the Hall of Fame logo and other markings.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hall of Fame Game canceled due to field concerns|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000681448/article/hall-of-fame-game-canceled-due-to-field-concerns|website=nfl.com|access-date=2016-08-08|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808162801/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000681448/article/hall-of-fame-game-canceled-due-to-field-concerns|archivedate=August 8, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* '''Week 8:''' The [[2016 Green Bay Packers season|Packers]]\u2013[[2016 Atlanta Falcons season|Falcons]] game, originally scheduled for 1:00&nbsp;p.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|ET]], was switched to 4:25&nbsp;p.m. ET in place of the originally-scheduled [[2016 Arizona Cardinals season|Cardinals]]\u2013[[2016 Carolina Panthers season|Panthers]] game, which was originally scheduled for 4:25&nbsp;p.m. ET (both games still on [[Fox NFL|Fox]]).<ref>{{cite web|title=Week 8 Schedule Change|url=https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/Week-8-Schedule-Change.aspx|website=nflcommunications.com|access-date=2016-10-13|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022063040/https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/Week-8-Schedule-Change.aspx|archivedate=October 22, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* '''Week 12:''' The [[2016 Kansas City Chiefs season|Chiefs]]\u2013[[2016 Denver Broncos season|Broncos]] game, originally scheduled for 4:25&nbsp;p.m. ET on [[NFL on CBS|CBS]], was flexed into the 8:30&nbsp;p.m. ET slot on [[NBC Sunday Night Football|NBC's Sunday Night Football]], in place of the originally-scheduled [[2016 New England Patriots season|Patriots]]\u2013[[2016 New York Jets season|Jets]] game, which was moved to 4:25&nbsp;p.m. ET on CBS.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/Week-12-November-27-Schedule-Change-Chiefs-Broncos-Moves-to-830-PM-ET-on-NBC.aspx|title=Week 12 (November 27) Schedule Change|website=nflcommunications.com|access-date=2016-11-14|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161115072710/https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/Week-12-November-27-Schedule-Change-Chiefs-Broncos-Moves-to-830-PM-ET-on-NBC.aspx|archivedate=November 15, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* '''Week 14:''' The [[2016 New Orleans Saints season|Saints]]\u2013[[2016 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Buccaneers]] game, originally scheduled for 1:00&nbsp;p.m. ET, was switched to 4:25&nbsp;p.m. ET, still on Fox. The [[2016 Chicago Bears season|Bears]]\u2013[[2016 Detroit Lions season|Lions]] game was \"cross-flexed\" from Fox to CBS, still at 1:00&nbsp;p.m. ET.<ref>{{cite web|title=Week 14 Schedule Change|url=https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/WEEK-14-(DECEMBER-11)-SCHEDULE-CHANGE.aspx|website=nflcommunications.com|publisher=[[National Football League|NFL]]|accessdate=29 November 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161130054107/https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/WEEK-14-(DECEMBER-11)-SCHEDULE-CHANGE.aspx|archivedate=November 30, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* '''Week 15:''' The [[2016 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Buccaneers]]\u2013[[2016 Dallas Cowboys season|Cowboys]] game, originally scheduled for 1:00&nbsp;p.m. ET on Fox, was flexed into the 8:30&nbsp;p.m. ET slot on NBC's Sunday Night Football, in place of the originally-scheduled [[2016 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Steelers]]\u2013[[2016 Cincinnati Bengals season|Bengals]] game, which was moved to 1:00&nbsp;p.m. ET on CBS.<ref>{{cite web|title=Week 15 Schedule Change|url=https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/Week-15-(December-18)-Scheduling-Change.aspx|website=nflcommunications.com|publisher=[[National Football League|NFL]]|accessdate=10 December 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224020934/https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/Week-15-(December-18)-Scheduling-Change.aspx|archivedate=December 24, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* '''Week 16:''' The [[2016 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Buccaneers]]\u2013[[2016 New Orleans Saints season|Saints]] game, originally scheduled for 1:00&nbsp;p.m. ET on Fox, was switched to 4:25&nbsp;p.m. ET (still on Fox).<ref>{{cite web|title=Week 16 Schedule Change|url=https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/WEEK-16-(DECEMBER-24)-SCHEDULE-CHANGE.aspx|website=nflcommunications.com|publisher=[[National Football League|NFL]]|accessdate=12 December 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224152709/https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/WEEK-16-(DECEMBER-24)-SCHEDULE-CHANGE.aspx|archivedate=December 24, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* '''Week 17:''' The [[2016 Green Bay Packers season|Packers]]\u2013[[2016 Detroit Lions season|Lions]] game, which was originally scheduled for 1:00&nbsp;p.m. ET on Fox, was selected for the final 8:30&nbsp;p.m. NBC Sunday Night Football game, which for the second consecutive season decided the [[NFC North]] division champion.  Also, the [[2016 New Orleans Saints season|Saints\u2013]][[2016 Atlanta Falcons season|Falcons]] game and the [[2016 New York Giants season|Giants\u2013]][[2016 Washington Redskins season|Redskins]] game were moved from 1:00&nbsp;p.m. ET to 4:25&nbsp;p.m. ET, with both games still on Fox.\n\n==Regular season standings==\n\n===Division===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n{{2016 AFC East standings}}\n{{2016 AFC North standings}}\n{{2016 AFC South standings}}\n{{2016 AFC West standings}}\n{{col-2}}\n{{2016 NFC East standings}}\n{{2016 NFC North standings}}\n{{2016 NFC South standings}}\n{{2016 NFC West standings}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Conference===\n{{2016 AFC standings}}\n{{2016 NFC standings}}\n\n==Postseason==\n{{main|2016\u201317 NFL playoffs}}\nThe 2016 playoffs began on the weekend of January 7\u20138, 2017 with the Wild Card playoff round. The four winners of these playoff games visited the top two seeded teams in each conference in the Divisional round games, which were played on the weekend of January 14\u201315, 2017. The winners of those games advanced to the Conference championship games, which will be held on January 22, 2017. The [[2017 Pro Bowl]] was held at the recently renovated [[Camping World Stadium]] (the former Citrus Bowl stadium) in [[Orlando, Florida]] on January 29, 2017 and aired on [[Monday Night Football|ESPN]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Soshnick|first=Scott|title=The NFL Pro Bowl Is Moving to Orlando|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-05-19/nfl-said-to-be-moving-pro-bowl-game-to-orlando-from-honolulu|accessdate=May 19, 2016|work=[[Bloomberg News]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160519221608/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-05-19/nfl-said-to-be-moving-pro-bowl-game-to-orlando-from-honolulu|archivedate=May 19, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Super Bowl LI]] was held on February 5, 2017 at [[NRG Stadium]] in [[Houston]] on Fox.\n\n===Playoffs bracket===\n{{2016\u201317 NFL playoffs}}\n\n==Notable events==\n\n===Deflategate===\nOn April 25, 2016, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit|2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals]] reinstated New England Patriots' [[quarterback]] [[Tom Brady]]'s four-game suspension for the 2016 regular season related to [[Deflategate]]; Brady dropped his appeal shortly thereafter and declined to take his case to the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]].<ref name=\"reinstated suspension\">{{cite web|last=Orr|first=Connor|title=Tom Brady's four-game suspension reinstated|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000655649/article/brady-fourgame-suspension-reinstated-by-us-appeals-court|website=[[NFL.com]]|date=April 25, 2016|accessdate=April 25, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426121909/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000655649/article/brady-fourgame-suspension-reinstated-by-us-appeals-court|archivedate=April 26, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Tom Brady has 4-game suspension upheld, not ready to accept ruling|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/15353950/tom-brady-new-england-patriots-four-game-suspension-deflategate-reinstated-appeals-court|accessdate=April 27, 2016|work=ESPN News Services|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=April 27, 2016|location=New York City|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426150714/http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/15353950/tom-brady-new-england-patriots-four-game-suspension-deflategate-reinstated-appeals-court|archivedate=April 26, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===National anthem protests===\n{{main|U.S. national anthem protests (2016\u2013present)}}\nIn 2016, several professional athletes have protested the [[The Star-Spangled Banner|United States national anthem]]. The protests began in the NFL after [[San Francisco 49ers]]' quarterback [[Colin Kaepernick]] sat during the anthem, as opposed to the tradition of standing, before a preseason game.<ref name=\"SB\">{{cite web|last1=Sandritter|first1=Mark|title=A timeline of Colin Kaepernick's national anthem protest and the NFL players who joined him|url=https://www.sbnation.com/2016/9/11/12869726/colin-kaepernick-national-anthem-protest-seahawks-brandon-marshall-nfl|publisher=SB Nation|accessdate=20 September 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160912110107/https://www.sbnation.com/2016/9/11/12869726/colin-kaepernick-national-anthem-protest-seahawks-brandon-marshall-nfl|archivedate=September 12, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Records, milestones, and notable statistics==\n\n;Week 1\n* [[Cam Newton]] scored his 44th career rushing touchdown, surpassing [[Steve Young]] for the most career rushing touchdowns by a quarterback in NFL history. Newton, who had scored a passing touchdown in the first quarter, also surpassed Young for the most career games with both a passing touchdown and a rushing touchdown by a quarterback in NFL history, with 32.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ingrassia|first=Nunzio|title=Cam Newton breaks a touchdown record held by Steve Young in first half|url=http://www.foxsports.com/nfl/story/cam-newton-breaks-a-touchdown-record-held-by-steve-young-in-first-half-090816.amp.html|publisher=[[Fox Sports Digital Media]]|website=[[Foxsports.com]]|accessdate=September 9, 2016|date=September 9, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915165639/http://www.foxsports.com/nfl/story/cam-newton-breaks-a-touchdown-record-held-by-steve-young-in-first-half-090816.amp.html|archivedate=September 15, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Drew Brees]] tied [[Peyton Manning]] for the most 400-yard passing games in a career (17 overall, regular season and postseason combined) by a quarterback.<ref>{{cite web|title=Saints Postgame Notes: September 11, 2016|url=http://www.neworleanssaints.com/news-and-events/article-1/Saints-Postgame-Notes-September-11-2016/f9e8fdf8-592b-48b2-a141-77dbe35ae388|publisher=neworleanssaints.com|accessdate=September 12, 2016|date=September 11, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920165413/http://www.neworleanssaints.com/news-and-events/article-1/Saints-Postgame-Notes-September-11-2016/f9e8fdf8-592b-48b2-a141-77dbe35ae388|archivedate=September 20, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n;Week 2\n* [[Drew Brees]] surpassed [[Dan Marino]] for third place on the NFL's all-time passing yards list.<ref>{{cite news|last=Canavan|first=Tom|title=Eli to Cruz sets up Giants win again, 16\u201313 over Saints|url=http://pro32.ap.org/article/eli-cruz-sets-giants-win-again-16-13-over-saints|accessdate=September 22, 2016|agency=Associated Press|work=AP Sports|date=September 18, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028190627/http://pro32.ap.org/article/eli-cruz-sets-giants-win-again-16-13-over-saints|archivedate=October 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n;Week 4\n* [[Frank Gore]] surpassed [[Marshall Faulk]] for 10th place on the NFL's all-time rushing yards list.<ref>{{cite news|last=Keefer|first=Zak|title=Colts sloppy early, comeback falls short|url=http://www.indystar.com/story/sports/nfl/colts/2016/10/02/colts-sloppy-early-comeback-falls-short/91326796/|accessdate=October 4, 2016|work=[[The Indianapolis Star]]|date=October 2, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003175701/http://www.indystar.com/story/sports/nfl/colts/2016/10/02/colts-sloppy-early-comeback-falls-short/91326796/|archivedate=October 3, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Matt Ryan (American football)|Matt Ryan]] and [[Julio Jones]] became the first quarterback/wide receiver duo in NFL history with 500+ passing yards and 300+ receiving yards in a single game.<ref>{{cite news|last=Odum|first=Charles|title=Ryan, Jones set records as Falcons beat Panthers 48\u201333|url=http://pro32.ap.org/article/ryan-jones-set-records-falcons-beat-panthers-48-33|accessdate=October 3, 2016|publisher=AP Sports|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=October 2, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003175754/http://pro32.ap.org/article/ryan-jones-set-records-falcons-beat-panthers-48-33|archivedate=October 3, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Matthew Stafford]] broke the NFL record previously held by [[Dan Marino]] for most passing yards in a quarterback's first 100 games, with 27,174.<ref>{{cite web|last=Meinke|first=Kyle|title=Lions QB Matthew Stafford breaks another NFL passing record|url=http://www.mlive.com/lions/index.ssf/2016/10/lions_qb_matthew_stafford_brea.html|website=MLive.com|publisher=[[Advance Publications]]|accessdate=October 4, 2016|date=October 2, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005064611/http://www.mlive.com/lions/index.ssf/2016/10/lions_qb_matthew_stafford_brea.html|archivedate=October 5, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n;Week 5\n* [[Bill Belichick]] won his 250th career game (including the post-season). He became the fourth head coach to reach this mark joining [[Don Shula]] (347 wins), [[George Halas]] (324) and [[Tom Landry]] (270).<ref>{{cite web|title=Seven From Sunday \u2013 Week 5|url=https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/SEVEN-FROM-SUNDAY-\u2013-WEEK-5-2016.aspx|website=nflcommunications.com|publisher=NFL Communications|accessdate=October 18, 2016|date=October 9, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022080449/https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/SEVEN-FROM-SUNDAY-%E2%80%93-WEEK-5-2016.aspx|archivedate=October 22, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n;Week 6\n* [[Dak Prescott]] broke the NFL record for most consecutive pass attempts without an interception to start a career, a record previously held by [[Tom Brady]] with 162 passes.<ref>{{cite news|last=Armas|first=Genaro|title=Cowboys keep rolling behind rookies Prescott, Elliott|url=http://pro32.ap.org/article/cowboys-keep-rolling-behind-rookies-prescott-elliott|accessdate=October 17, 2016|agency=Associated Press|work=AP Sports|date=October 17, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019010634/http://pro32.ap.org/article/cowboys-keep-rolling-behind-rookies-prescott-elliott|archivedate=October 19, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He ran his streak to 176 pass attempts before throwing his first interception.<ref>{{cite news|last=Reyes|first=Lorenzo|title=Dak Prescott amplifies Cowboys' Tony Romo question in win over Packers|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/cowboys/2016/10/16/dak-prescott-tony-romo-dallas-qb-green-bay-packers/92218112/|accessdate=October 17, 2016|work=[[USA Today]]|date=October 16, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161017013548/http://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/cowboys/2016/10/16/dak-prescott-tony-romo-dallas-qb-green-bay-packers/92218112/|archivedate=October 17, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Tom Brady]] became the fourth quarterback in NFL history to record 5,000 career pass completions, joining [[Brett Favre]], [[Peyton Manning]], and [[Drew Brees]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Ortiz|first=Robert|title=Tom Brady becomes fourth QB to reach 5,000 career completions|url=http://sportsnaut.com/2016/10/tom-brady-becomes-fourth-qb-reach-5000-career-completions/|accessdate=October 17, 2016|website=Sportsnaut|date=October 16, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018210607/http://sportsnaut.com/2016/10/tom-brady-becomes-fourth-qb-reach-5000-career-completions/|archivedate=October 18, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Drew Brees]] set an NFL record for the most regular season 400-yard passing games in a career by a quarterback with 15.<ref>{{cite news|last=Martel|first=Brett|title=Brees leads Saints past slumping Panthers, 41\u201338|url=http://pro32.ap.org/article/brees-leads-saints-past-slumping-panthers-41-38|accessdate=October 17, 2016|agency=Associated Press|work=AP Sports|date=October 16, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019005448/http://pro32.ap.org/article/brees-leads-saints-past-slumping-panthers-41-38|archivedate=October 19, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Brees also became the sixth player to record 50,000 passing yards with one team, joining [[Peyton Manning]] (Colts), [[Brett Favre]] (Packers), [[Dan Marino]] (Dolphins), [[Tom Brady]] (Patriots) and [[John Elway]] (Broncos).<ref>{{cite news|last=Erickson|first=Joel|title=Big day from Drew Brees leads 'battle-tested' Saints over Carolina Panthers|url=http://www.theadvocate.com/new_orleans/sports/saints/article_fc4113b4-93d8-11e6-9d50-37985d0db8cd.html?sr_source=lift_amplify|accessdate=October 17, 2016|work=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|The Advocate]]|date=October 16, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018214712/http://www.theadvocate.com/new_orleans/sports/saints/article_fc4113b4-93d8-11e6-9d50-37985d0db8cd.html?sr_source=lift_amplify|archivedate=October 18, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n;Week 7\n* [[Jay Ajayi]] rushed for 214 yards. With his 204-yard rushing output the week before, Ajayi became the fourth player in NFL history to rush for at least 200 yards in consecutive games, joining [[O.J. Simpson]] (who accomplished the feat twice), [[Earl Campbell]] and [[Ricky Williams]].<ref>{{cite web|title=SEVEN FROM SUNDAY \u2013 WEEK 7|url=https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/SEVEN-FROM-SUNDAY-\u2013-WEEK-7.aspx|website=NFLCommunications.com|publisher=NFL Enterprises, L.P.|accessdate=November 8, 2016|date=October 23, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025070352/https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/SEVEN-FROM-SUNDAY-%E2%80%93-WEEK-7.aspx|archivedate=October 25, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Adam Vinatieri]] set a new NFL record for most consecutive regular season field-goals made with 43, breaking the record that was held by [[Mike Vanderjagt]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Walker|first=Teresa|title=Luck still perfect vs. Titans as Colts pull out 34\u201326 win|url=http://pro32.ap.org/article/luck-still-perfect-vs-titans-colts-pull-out-34-26-win|accessdate=November 8, 2016|agency=Associated Press|work=AP Sports|date=October 23, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161109083635/http://pro32.ap.org/article/luck-still-perfect-vs-titans-colts-pull-out-34-26-win|archivedate=November 9, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> His streak ended at 44 after a miss in Week 11.<ref>{{cite news|last=Marot|first=Michael|title=Colts get fast start and hold off charging Titans 24\u201317|url=http://pro32.ap.org/article/colts-get-fast-start-and-hold-charging-titans-24-17|accessdate=November 23, 2016|agency=Associated Press|work=AP Sports|date=November 20, 2016|location=Indianapolis|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161122190709/http://pro32.ap.org/article/colts-get-fast-start-and-hold-charging-titans-24-17|archivedate=November 22, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Matt Ryan (American football)|Matt Ryan]] set an NFL record for the most consecutive games with at least 200 passing yards, with 46.<ref>{{cite news|last=Odum|first=Charles|title=Chargers beat Falcons 33\u201330 in OT on Lambo's 42-yard FG|url=http://pro32.ap.org/article/chargers-beat-falcons-33-30-ot-lambos-42-yard-fg|accessdate=November 8, 2016|agency=Associated Press|work=AP Sports|date=October 23, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161109022311/http://pro32.ap.org/article/chargers-beat-falcons-33-30-ot-lambos-42-yard-fg|archivedate=November 9, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n;Week 8\n* The [[2016 Washington Redskins season|Redskins]]\u2013[[2016 Cincinnati Bengals season|Bengals]] match ended in a 27\u201327 tie.  It was the first time an [[NFL International Series|International Series]] game had ended in a tie (and the first such game to have gone into overtime).  It also was the first time since [[1997 NFL season|1997]] where two games ended in a tie in the same season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pogatchnik|first=Shawn|title=Redskins, Bengals battle to 27\u201327 tie in London|url=http://pro32.ap.org/article/redskins-bengals-battle-27-27-tie-london|accessdate=November 1, 2016|agency=Associated Press|work=AP Sports|date=October 30, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161031153945/http://pro32.ap.org/article/redskins-bengals-battle-27-27-tie-london|archivedate=October 31, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* The [[2016 Oakland Raiders season|Raiders]] were penalized 23 times for 200 yards, setting a new NFL record for the most penalties against a team in a single game.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tafur|first=Vic|title=Raiders overcome themselves \u2014 and Bucs \u2014 in OT win|url=http://www.sfgate.com/raiders/article/Raiders-overcome-themselves-and-Bucs-in-OT-win-10423640.php|accessdate=November 8, 2016|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|date=October 30, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161107230724/http://www.sfgate.com/raiders/article/Raiders-overcome-themselves-and-Bucs-in-OT-win-10423640.php|archivedate=November 7, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n;Week 9\n* The [[San Francisco 49ers]] set an NFL record for allowing an opponent's running back to run for 100 or more yards in seven consecutive games.<ref>{{cite web|last=Young|first=Shalise|title=49ers' run defense set sad new record on Sunday vs. Saints|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/49ers-run-defense-set-sad-new-record-on-sunday-vs-saints-155130253.html|website=sports.yahoo.com|publisher=[[Yahoo! Sports]]|accessdate=November 7, 2016|date=November 7, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161107223111/http://sports.yahoo.com/news/49ers-run-defense-set-sad-new-record-on-sunday-vs-saints-155130253.html|archivedate=November 7, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n;Week 10\n* [[Stefon Diggs]] became the first player in NFL history to have at least 13 catches in consecutive games.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vensel|first=Matt|title=Familiar story: Vikings lose another game, another body on O-line|url=http://www.startribune.com/vikings-fast-start-now-a-distant-memory-after-26-20-loss-to-redskins/401018985/#1|accessdate=November 14, 2016|work=[[Star Tribune]]|date=November 14, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161114234725/http://www.startribune.com/vikings-fast-start-now-a-distant-memory-after-26-20-loss-to-redskins/401018985/#1|archivedate=November 14, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* For the first time in NFL history, two different games on the same day, the [[2016 Dallas Cowboys season|Cowboys]]\u2013[[2016 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Steelers]] matchup and the [[2016 Seattle Seahawks season|Seahawks]]\u2013[[2016 New England Patriots season|Patriots]] matchup, involved at least seven different lead changes.<ref>{{cite web |title=THE WEEK THAT WAS \u2013 WEEK 10 |url=https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/THE-WEEK-THAT-WAS-%E2%80%93-WEEK-10.aspx |date=November 15, 2016 |accessdate=November 15, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161116103554/https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/THE-WEEK-THAT-WAS-%E2%80%93-WEEK-10.aspx |archivedate=November 16, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n;Week 11\n* A single-day record twelve [[point after touchdown]] attempts were missed, including three in domed stadiums.<ref>{{cite web |author=Hanzus, Dan |title=NFL kickers miss record 12 extra-point attempts Sunday |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000742721/article/nfl-kickers-miss-record-11-extrapoint-attempts-today |work=NFL |date=November 20, 2016 |accessdate=November 20, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161121174254/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000742721/article/nfl-kickers-miss-record-11-extrapoint-attempts-today |archivedate=November 21, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* The [[Dallas Cowboys]] gained 417 total net yards, marking the team's eighth consecutive game with at least 400 yards, tied for the longest single-season streak in NFL history ([[2007 New England Patriots season|2007 New England Patriots]] and [[2013 Denver Broncos season|2013 Denver Broncos]]).<ref name=\"wk11Seven\">{{cite web|title=SEVEN FROM SUNDAY \u2013 WEEK 11|url=https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/SEVEN-FROM-SUNDAY-\u2013-WEEK-11.aspx|website=NFLCommunications.com|publisher=NFL Enterprises, L.P.|accessdate=November 23, 2016|date=November 21, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161122071619/https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/SEVEN-FROM-SUNDAY-%E2%80%93-WEEK-11.aspx|archivedate=November 22, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Steve Smith Sr.]] reached 1,000 catches, becoming the 14th player in NFL history to reach this mark.<ref>{{cite news|last=Zrebiec|first=Jeff|title=Ravens' Steve Smith makes his 1,000th career catch|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/ravens/bal-smith-smith-makes-his-1-000th-career-catch-20161120-story.html|accessdate=November 23, 2016|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|date=November 20, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123203749/http://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/ravens/bal-smith-smith-makes-his-1-000th-career-catch-20161120-story.html|archivedate=November 23, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n;Week 12\n* With the [[New England Patriots]]' victory, [[Tom Brady]] joined [[Peyton Manning]] as the second starting quarterback in NFL history to record 200 combined regular season and postseason wins.<ref>{{cite news|last=Reyes|first=Lorenzo|title=Tom Brady revels in record-tying 200th win with Patriots|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/patriots/2016/11/27/tom-brady-record-qb-wins-new-england/94529174/|accessdate=November 28, 2016|work=[[USA Today]]|date=November 28, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128072304/http://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/patriots/2016/11/27/tom-brady-record-qb-wins-new-england/94529174/|archivedate=November 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The Patriots' victory made them the first former [[American Football League]] franchise to record 500 all-time victories, including playoffs.<ref name=\"Brady ties Manning with 200th win, Patriots beat Jets 22-17\">{{cite news|last=Waszak|first=Dennis|title=Brady ties Manning with 200th win, Patriots beat Jets 22\u201317|url=http://pro32.ap.org/article/brady-ties-manning-200th-win-patriots-beat-jets-22-17|accessdate=November 28, 2016|agency=Associated Press|work=AP Sports|date=November 27, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161128151443/http://pro32.ap.org/article/brady-ties-manning-200th-win-patriots-beat-jets-22-17|archivedate=November 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Brady also became only the fifth quarterback to record 60,000 regular season passing yards, joining [[Peyton Manning]], [[Brett Favre]], [[Drew Brees]] and [[Dan Marino]].<ref name=\"Brady ties Manning with 200th win, Patriots beat Jets 22-17\" />\n\n;Week 13\n* With the Patriots' victory, [[Tom Brady]] broke [[Peyton Manning]]'s record of most career wins by a quarterback (regular season and playoffs) in NFL history with his 201st win.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hightower|first=Kyle|title=Brady breaks QB wins record, Patriots beat Rams 26\u201310|url=http://pro32.ap.org/article/brady-breaks-qb-wins-record-patriots-beat-rams-26-10|accessdate=December 5, 2016|agency=Associated Press|work=AP Sports|date=December 4, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161205131148/http://pro32.ap.org/article/brady-breaks-qb-wins-record-patriots-beat-rams-26-10|archivedate=December 5, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Larry Fitzgerald]] became the youngest player in NFL history (33 years, 95 days) to reach 1,100 career catches.<ref>{{cite news|last=Baum|first=Bob|title=Palmer, Johnson lead Cardinals past Redskins|url=http://pro32.ap.org/article/palmer-johnson-lead-cardinals-past-redskins|accessdate=December 6, 2016|agency=Associated Press|work=AP Sports|date=December 4, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206173506/http://pro32.ap.org/article/palmer-johnson-lead-cardinals-past-redskins|archivedate=December 6, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n;Week 14\n* [[Matthew Stafford]] recorded his eighth fourth quarter comeback win of the season, surpassing the previous record held by [[Peyton Manning]], who led the Indianapolis Colts to seven fourth quarter comeback wins during the 2009 season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lage|first=Larry|title=Stafford runs for go-ahead TD in Lions' 20\u201317 win over Bears|url=http://pro32.ap.org/article/stafford-runs-go-ahead-td-lions-20-17-win-over-bears|access-date=December 12, 2016|agency=Associated Press|work=AP Sports|date=December 11, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220150028/http://pro32.ap.org/article/stafford-runs-go-ahead-td-lions-20-17-win-over-bears|archive-date=December 20, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Anquan Boldin]] moved past [[Andre Johnson]] for tenth on the [[List of National Football League receiving yards leaders|NFL's all-time receptions list]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Meinke|first=Kyle|title=Anquan Boldin moves into top 10 in career catches with big TD snag|url=http://www.mlive.com/lions/index.ssf/2016/12/anquan_boldin_improves_hall_of.html|website=MLive.com|publisher=[[Advance Publications]]|access-date=December 12, 2016|date=December 11, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201034412/http://www.mlive.com/lions/index.ssf/2016/12/anquan_boldin_improves_hall_of.html|archive-date=December 1, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n;Week 15\n* The [[New England Patriots]] clinched their eighth consecutive [[AFC East]] title.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Lindsay|title=Patriots crack Broncos to clinch AFC East, first-round bye|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/patriots/2016/12/18/new-england-afc-east-denver-broncos/95596208/|accessdate=December 20, 2016|work=[[USA Today]]|date=December 19, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161219230027/http://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/patriots/2016/12/18/new-england-afc-east-denver-broncos/95596208/|archivedate=December 19, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> They surpassed the [[Los Angeles Rams]], who won the [[NFC West]] division title every year from [[1973 Los Angeles Rams season|1973]] to [[1979 Los Angeles Rams season|1979]], for the most consecutive division titles won by any franchise in NFL history.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wesseling|first=Chris|title=Patriots top Broncos, clinch AFC East, first-round bye|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000759222/article/patriots-top-broncos-clinch-afc-east-firstround-bye|website=NFL.com|publisher=NFL Enterprises, L.P.|accessdate=December 20, 2016|date=December 18, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161219164004/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000759222/article/patriots-top-broncos-clinch-afc-east-firstround-bye|archivedate=December 19, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n;Week 16\n* The [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] recorded the 600th regular-season victory in franchise history, joining the [[Chicago Bears]], [[Green Bay Packers]], and [[New York Giants]] as the only teams in NFL history to reach this mark.<ref>{{cite web|title=THE WEEK THAT WAS \u2013 WEEK 16|url=https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/THE-WEEK-THAT-WAS---WEEK-16--.aspx|website=NFLCommunications.com|publisher=NFL Enterprises, L.P.|access-date=December 28, 2016|date=December 27, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161228221435/https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/THE-WEEK-THAT-WAS---WEEK-16--.aspx|archive-date=December 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Bill Belichick]] won his 200th career regular-season game as head coach of the [[New England Patriots]].  Belichick became the fifth coach to reach 200 regular-season wins with one team, joining [[George Halas]], [[Don Shula]], [[Tom Landry]] and [[Curly Lambeau]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Hightower|first=Kyle|title=Patriots close in on AFC top seed with 41\u20133 win over Jets|url=http://pro32.ap.org/node/700759|accessdate=December 28, 2016|agency=Associated Press|work=AP Sports|date=December 24, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161228200755/http://pro32.ap.org/node/700759|archivedate=December 28, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Matt Ryan (American football)|Matt Ryan]] threw a touchdown pass to his 13th different receiver of the season, an NFL record.\n\n;Week 17\n* [[Matthew Stafford]] surpassed 30,000 career passing yards in his 109th game, surpassing [[Dan Marino]] and [[Kurt Warner]] for the fastest quarterback to reach that mark.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lage|first=Larry|title=Rodgers-led Packers beat Lions 31\u201324 to win NFC North|url=http://pro32.ap.org/article/rodgers-led-packers-beat-lions-31-24-win-nfc-north|accessdate=January 2, 2017|agency=Associated Press|work=AP Sports|date=January 2, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170103002558/http://pro32.ap.org/article/rodgers-led-packers-beat-lions-31-24-win-nfc-north|archivedate=January 3, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Sam Bradford]] achieved a 71.6 completion percentage, surpassing [[Drew Brees]] for the record for [[List of National Football League annual pass completion percentage leaders|highest completion percentage in a season]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Goldberg|first=Rob|title=Sam Bradford  Sets NFL Record for Single-Season Completion Percentage|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2684679-sam-bradford-sets-nfl-record-for-single-season-completion-percentage|accessdate=January 1, 2017|work=[[Bleacher Report]]|date=January 1, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170102064511/http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2684679-sam-bradford-sets-nfl-record-for-single-season-completion-percentage|archivedate=January 2, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Postseason===\n\n;Division Round\n* The Patriots advanced to their sixth consecutive AFC Championship Game, surpassing the [[1973 Oakland Raiders season|1973]]\u2013[[1977 Oakland Raiders season|1977]] Oakland Raiders for the most consecutive appearances in a conference championship game in history.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hightower|first=Kyle|title=Lewis scores 3 TDS, Pats advance to AFC title game 34\u201316|url=http://pro32.ap.org/article/lewis-scores-3-tds-pats-advance-afc-title-game-34-16|accessdate=January 17, 2017|agency=Associated Press|work=AP Sports|date=January 15, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116184917/http://pro32.ap.org/article/lewis-scores-3-tds-pats-advance-afc-title-game-34-16|archivedate=January 16, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Chris Boswell]] made a postseason record six field goals during the Steelers' win over the Chiefs.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilner|first=Barry|title=Steelers hold off Chiefs on Boswell's 6 field goals, 18\u201316|url=http://pro32.ap.org/article/steelers-hold-chiefs-boswells-6-field-goals-18-16|accessdate=January 17, 2017|agency=Associated Press|work=AP Sports|date=January 16, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170117153031/http://pro32.ap.org/article/steelers-hold-chiefs-boswells-6-field-goals-18-16|archivedate=January 17, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Dak Prescott]] became the first rookie starting QB to throw three touchdown passes in a postseason game in the Super Bowl era.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Lindsay|title=Dak Prescott shines, but playoff debut spoiled by Aaron Rodgers, Packers|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/cowboys/2017/01/15/dak-prescott-tony-romo-dallas-jerry-jones/96629178/|accessdate=January 17, 2017|work=[[USA Today]]|date=January 15, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170117011113/http://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/cowboys/2017/01/15/dak-prescott-tony-romo-dallas-jerry-jones/96629178/|archivedate=January 17, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* Patriots' RB [[Dion Lewis]] became the first player in NFL history to score a rushing, receiving and kickoff return touchdown in a playoff game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/nfl/story/_/id/18477954/new-england-patriots-dion-lewis-scores-kickoff-return-receiving-rushing-touchdowns|title=Pats' Lewis makes playoff history with 3-TD night|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170124170443/http://www.espn.co.uk/nfl/story/_/id/18477954/new-england-patriots-dion-lewis-scores-kickoff-return-receiving-rushing-touchdowns|archivedate=January 24, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n;Super Bowl LI\n* [[Super Bowl LI]] marked an NFL record seventh Super Bowl appearance for [[Tom Brady]] and [[Bill Belichick]] as a QB-head coach duo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/nfl/story/_/id/18534854/tom-brady-bill-belichick-make-nfl-history-record-7th-super-bowl-appearance|title=They're back: Brady, Belichick into record 7th SB|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180105152502/http://www.espn.co.uk/nfl/story/_/id/18534854/tom-brady-bill-belichick-make-nfl-history-record-7th-super-bowl-appearance|archivedate=January 5, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* Super Bowl LI also marked the [[New England Patriots]]' ninth Super Bowl appearance, breaking a record shared with the [[Dallas Cowboys]], [[Denver Broncos]], and [[Pittsburgh Steelers]].\n* [[Tom Brady]]'s 43 pass completions, 62 pass attempts, and 466 passing yards all set new single game Super Bowl records.\n* For the first time in NFL history, the Super Bowl went into overtime.\n* After trailing 28\u20133, the Patriots won the game, 34\u201328, completing the largest comeback win in both team history and Super Bowl history.\n* Brady won his fifth Super Bowl, which tied defensive player [[Charles Haley]] for the most Super Bowl victories won by a player, and he became the first quarterback in NFL history to do so.\n* Brady was named the [[Super Bowl MVP]]. This was the fourth time Brady won the award, giving him more career Super Bowl MVP awards than any other player in NFL history.\n* The [[Atlanta Falcons]] became the first losing team in Super Bowl history to return an interception for a touchdown; teams returning an interception for a touchdown in the Super Bowl had been a perfect 12\u20130.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2017/02/06/5-mind-blowing-facts-to-sum-up-patriots-super-bowl-stunner |title=5 Mind-Blowing Facts To Sum Up Patriots\u2019 Super Bowl Stunner |publisher=CBS Boston |date=February 6, 2017 |access-date=February 6, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170208171228/http://boston.cbslocal.com/2017/02/06/5-mind-blowing-facts-to-sum-up-patriots-super-bowl-stunner/ |archive-date=February 8, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Regular season statistical leaders==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Individual<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/stats/player |title=NFL Stats: Player |work=NFL.com |accessdate=December 13, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090111214603/http://www.nfl.com/stats/player |archivedate=January 11, 2009 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref>\n|-\n|'''Scoring leader'''|| [[Matt Bryant]], Atlanta (158)\n|-\n|'''Most Field Goals Made'''|| [[Justin Tucker]], Baltimore (38 FGs)\n|-\n|'''Touchdowns'''|| [[David Johnson (running back)|David Johnson]], Arizona (20 TDs)\n|-\n|'''Rushing'''|| [[Ezekiel Elliot]], Dallas (1,631 yards)\n|-\n|'''Passing yards'''|| [[Drew Brees]], New Orleans (5,208 yards)\n|-\n|'''Passing touchdowns'''|| [[Aaron Rodgers]], Green Bay (40 TDs)\n|-\n|'''Passer rating'''|| [[Matt Ryan (American football)|Matt Ryan]], Atlanta (117.1 rating)\n|-\n|'''Pass receptions'''|| [[Larry Fitzgerald]], Arizona (107 catches)\n|-\n|'''Pass receiving yards'''|| [[T.Y. Hilton]], Indianapolis (1,448 yards)\n|-\n|'''Combined tackles'''|| [[Bobby Wagner]], Seattle (168 tackles)\n|-\n|'''Interceptions'''|| [[Casey Hayward]], San Diego (7)\n|-\n|'''Punting'''|| [[Johnny Hekker]], Los Angeles (4,680 yards, 47.8 average yards)\n|-\n|-'''Kick & punt return yards'''|| [[Alex Erickson]], Cincinnati (1,006 yards)\n|-\n|'''Sacks'''|| [[Vic Beasley]], Atlanta (15.5)\n|}\n\n==Awards==\n\n===Individual season awards===\n{{Further|6th Annual NFL Honors}}\n\nThe [[6th Annual NFL Honors]], saluting the best players and plays from 2016 season, was held at the [[Wortham Theater Center]] in [[Houston, Texas]] on February 4, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Keegan\u2013Michael Key to host NFL Honors in Houston|url=https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/Keegan-Michael-Key-to-Host-NFL-Honors-at-Wortham-Theater-Center-in-Houston.aspx|website=nflcommunications.com|publisher=[[NFL]]|date=January 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Award !! Winner !! Position !! Team\n|-\n| [[National Football League Most Valuable Player Award|AP Most Valuable Player]] || [[Matt Ryan (American football)|Matt Ryan]] || Quarterback || [[2016 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]]\n|-\n| [[Associated Press NFL Offensive Player of the Year Award|AP Offensive Player of the Year]] || [[Matt Ryan (American football)|Matt Ryan]] || Quarterback || [[2016 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]]\n|-\n| [[National Football League Defensive Player of the Year Award|AP Defensive Player of the Y