Raiders)\n|-\n!13\n| [[Joe Flacco]]<br />([[Baltimore Ravens|Ravens]])\n| Latavius Murray<br />(Raiders)\n| Ezekiel Elliott<br />(Cowboys)\n| [[Khalil Mack]]<br />(Raiders)\n|-\n!14\n| Aaron Rodgers<br />(Packers)\n| [[Le'Veon Bell]]<br />(Steelers)\n| Ezekiel Elliott<br />(Cowboys)\n| [[Keith Tandy]]<br />(Buccaneers)\n|-\n!15\n| Matt Ryan<br />(Falcons)\n| [[Devonta Freeman]]<br />([[Atlanta Falcons|Falcons]])\n| Ezekiel Elliott<br />(Cowboys)\n| [[Sebastian Janikowski]]<br />(Raiders)\n|-\n!16\n| Aaron Rodgers<br />(Packers)\n| Jay Ajayi<br />(Dolphins)\n| Dak Prescott<br />(Cowboys)\n| [[Antonio Brown]]<br />([[Pittsburgh Steelers|Steelers]])\n|-\n!17\n| Matt Ryan<br />(Falcons)\n| [[Isaiah Crowell]]<br />([[Cleveland Browns|Browns]])\n| [[Tyreek Hill]]<br />([[Kansas City Chiefs|Chiefs]])\n| [[Mike Evans (wide receiver)|Mike Evans]]<br />(Buccaneers)\n|}\n\n|  style=\"padding-left:40px;\" |\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%; text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Month\n!colspan=2|Rookie of the Month\n|-\n!Offensive\n!Defensive\n|-\n!Sept.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/NFL-Rookies-2016.aspx |title=NFL Rookies of the Month \u2013 September |website=Nflcommunications.com |accessdate=2016-12-23 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104042138/https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/NFL-Rookies-2016.aspx |archivedate=November 4, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| [[Carson Wentz]]<br />([[Philadelphia Eagles|Eagles]])\n| [[Deion Jones]]<br />([[Atlanta Falcons|Falcons]])\n|-\n!Oct.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/NFL-Rookies-of-the-Month---October--.aspx |title=NFL Rookies of the Month \u2013 October |website=Nflcommunications.com |accessdate=2016-12-23 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104043440/https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/NFL-Rookies-of-the-Month---October--.aspx |archivedate=November 4, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| [[Ezekiel Elliott]]<br />([[Dallas Cowboys|Cowboys]])\n| [[Joey Bosa]]<br />([[San Diego Chargers|Chargers]])\n|-\n!Nov.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/NFL-Rookies-of-the-Month---November-.aspx |title=NFL Rookies of the Month \u2013 November |website=Nflcommunications.com |accessdate=2016-12-23 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202045146/https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/NFL-Rookies-of-the-Month---November-.aspx |archivedate=December 2, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| [[Dak Prescott]]<br />(Cowboys)\n| [[Noah Spence]]<br />([[Tampa Bay Buccaneers|Buccaneers]])\n|-\n!Dec.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/NFL-Rookies-of-the-Month---December-.aspx |title=NFL Rookies of the Month \u2013 December |website=Nflcommunications.com |accessdate=2017-01-05 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170106011829/https://nflcommunications.com/Pages/NFL-Rookies-of-the-Month---December-.aspx |archivedate=January 6, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| [[Jordan Howard]]<br />([[Chicago Bears|Bears]])\n| Joey Bosa<br />(Chargers)\n|}\n|}\n\n==Head coach/front office personnel changes==\n\n===Head coach===\n\n====Offseason====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Team\n!2015 head coach\n!2015 interim\n!2016 replacement\n!Reason for leaving\n!Notes\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Cleveland Browns]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Mike Pettine]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Hue Jackson]]\n| rowspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |Fired\n|Pettine compiled a record of 10\u201322 ({{winning percentage|10|22}}) in two years with the Browns, finishing in last place in the AFC North both years. After putting up a promising record of 7\u20139 the season before, the team, marred by the actions of [[Johnny Manziel]] off the field, regressed heavily, forcing the Browns to hire their fifth head coach in eight seasons. The decision to fire Pettine came the day before the end of the regular season.<ref name=\"Brownsfired\">{{cite web|last=Rosenthal|first=Gregg|title=Cleveland Browns fire Mike Pettine, GM Ray Farmer|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000614532/article/browns-gm-ray-farmer-out-in-cleveland|website=NFL.com|date=January 3, 2016|accessdate=January 3, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160104012019/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000614532/article/browns-gm-ray-farmer-out-in-cleveland|archivedate=January 4, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\nOn January 13, the Browns hired Jackson as their head coach. Jackson spent most of the past two seasons as the offensive coordinator for the [[Cincinnati Bengals]] and had previously served as head coach for the [[Oakland Raiders]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wesseling|first1=Chris|title=Cleveland Browns hire Hue Jackson as head coach|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000621189/article/cleveland-browns-hire-hue-jackson-as-head-coach|website=NFL.com|accessdate=13 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160116091451/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000621189/article/cleveland-browns-hire-hue-jackson-as-head-coach|archivedate=January 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Miami Dolphins]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Joe Philbin]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Dan Campbell]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Adam Gase]]\n|Philbin compiled a record of 24\u201328 ({{winning percentage|24|28}}), with no playoff appearances, in 3\u00bc seasons as head coach of the Dolphins. The Dolphins were expected to be contenders for a playoff position in 2015 but grossly underachieved, starting the season 1\u20133, which led to Philbin's firing. Philbin joined the [[Indianapolis Colts]] as offensive line coach for 2016. Campbell, the team's tight ends coach, took over for the rest of the season; following the season, he joined the [[New Orleans Saints]] as tight ends coach.<ref>{{cite web|last=Walker|first=James|title=Dolphins fire coach Joe Philbin after team stumbles to 1\u20133 start|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/13814560/miami-dolphins-fire-joe-philbin|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=December 29, 2015|date=October 5, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160125063747/http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/13814560/miami-dolphins-fire-joe-philbin|archivedate=January 25, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\nOn January 9, the Dolphins hired Gase as their head coach. Gase had spent the past season as the offensive coordinator for the [[Chicago Bears]]; at age 37, Gase became the youngest active head coach in the NFL.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sessler|first1=Marc|title=Miami Dolphins hire Adam Gase as new head coach|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000619758/article/miami-dolphins-hire-adam-gase-as-new-head-coach|website=NFL.com|accessdate=10 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109215650/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000619758/article/miami-dolphins-hire-adam-gase-as-new-head-coach|archivedate=January 9, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Philadelphia Eagles]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Chip Kelly]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Pat Shurmur]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Doug Pederson]]\n|Kelly was released on December 29, 2015, one week prior to the end of the regular season, following the Eagles being eliminated from playoff contention. He finished with a record of 26\u201321 ({{winning percentage|26|21}}) and one playoff appearance (a single loss in 2013) over almost three seasons. Heading into 2015, Kelly made several controversial roster moves as general manager that didn't pan out, leading to his firing. Offensive Coordinator (and former [[Cleveland Browns]] head coach) Pat Shurmur served as interim replacement for week 17.<ref name=\"Eaglesfired\">{{cite web|last=Rosenthal|first=Gregg|title=Chip Kelly released by Philadelphia Eagles|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000612168/article/philadelphia-eagles-let-go-of-chip-kelly|website=NFL.com|accessdate=2015-12-30|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160101205114/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000612168/article/philadelphia-eagles-let-go-of-chip-kelly|archivedate=January 1, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Shurmur finished 1\u20130 as the Eagles head coach, and was a frontrunner in the Eagles head coaching race along with [[Tom Coughlin]] and [[Doug Pederson]]; following the season, he joined the [[Minnesota Vikings]] as tight ends coach and later offensive coordinator after the sudden resignation of [[Norv Turner]].\nOn January 18, the Eagles hired Pederson as their head coach. Pederson had spent the previous three season as offensive coordinator for the [[Kansas City Chiefs]], and also was a former QB for the Eagles.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wesseling|first=Chris|title=Philadelphia Eagles hire Doug Pederson as coach|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000622612/article/philadelphia-eagles-hire-doug-pederson-as-coach|website=NFL.com|accessdate=January 18, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160120142223/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000622612/article/philadelphia-eagles-hire-doug-pederson-as-coach|archivedate=January 20, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[San Francisco 49ers]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Jim Tomsula]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Chip Kelly]]\n| Tomsula compiled a record of 5\u201311 ({{winning percentage|5|11}}) in his lone full season as head coach of the 49ers.<ref>{{cite web|title=San Francisco 49ers fire coach Jim Tomsula|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000616007/article/san-francisco-49ers-fire-coach-jim-tomsula|website=nfl.com|date=January 3, 2016|accessdate=January 3, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160104063418/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000616007/article/san-francisco-49ers-fire-coach-jim-tomsula|archivedate=January 4, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\nOn January 14, the 49ers hired Kelly as their head coach. Kelly had spent the previous three seasons as head coach for the [[Philadelphia Eagles]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Patra|first1=Kevin|title=San Francisco 49ers hire Chip Kelly as head coach|url=http://www.NFL.com/news/story/0ap3000000622478/article/san-francisco-49ers-hire-chip-kelly-as-head-coach|website=NFL.com|date=January 14, 2016|accessdate=January 14, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114232425/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000622478/article/san-francisco-49ers-hire-chip-kelly-as-head-coach|archivedate=January 14, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Lovie Smith]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Dirk Koetter]]\n|Smith compiled a record of 8\u201324 ({{winning percentage|8|24}}), with no playoff appearances, in two years with the Buccaneers, finishing in last place in the NFC South both years.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wesseling|first1=Chris|title=Tampa Bay Buccaneers fire Lovie Smith|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000618589/article/tampa-bay-buccaneers-fire-lovie-smith|website=NFL.com|date=January 6, 2016|accessdate=January 6, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107083057/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000618589/article/tampa-bay-buccaneers-fire-lovie-smith|archivedate=January 7, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Smith moved to the college ranks, becoming the head coach of the University of [[Illinois Fighting Illini football]] team.\nOn January 14, Koetter was promoted to head coach after serving as offensive coordinator with the team since 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hanzus|first1=Dan|title=Buccaneers promote OC Dirk Koetter to head coach|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000622328/article/buccaneers-promote-oc-dirk-koetter-to-head-coach|website=NFL.com|date=January 14, 2016|accessdate=January 14, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160116102233/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000622328/article/buccaneers-promote-oc-dirk-koetter-to-head-coach|archivedate=January 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Tennessee Titans]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Ken Whisenhunt]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=2 |[[Mike Mularkey]]\n|Whisenhunt compiled a record of 3\u201320 ({{winning percentage|3|20}}), with no playoff appearances, in 1\u00bd seasons as head coach of the Titans. After an impressive opening day win, the Titans lost six straight, resulting in Whisenhunt's dismissal. Mularkey, the team's tight ends coach, took over as interim head coach.  Mularkey's previous head coaching experience includes two seasons with the [[Buffalo Bills]] (2004\u201305) and one season with the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] (2012).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Orr|first1=Conor|title=Tennessee Titans fire head coach Ken Whisenhunt|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000572205/article/whisenhunt-relieved-of-duties-as-titans-head-coach|website=NFL.com|accessdate=2015-12-29|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106164651/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000572205/article/whisenhunt-relieved-of-duties-as-titans-head-coach|archivedate=January 6, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> For 2016, Whisenhunt joined the [[San Diego Chargers]] as offensive coordinator.\nOn January 16, Mularkey shed the interim tag and was hired as the full-time head coach.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sessler|first1=Marc|title=Mike Mularkey sheds interim tag, named Titans coach|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000623006/article/mike-mularkey-sheds-interim-tag-named-titans-coach|website=NFL.com|accessdate=17 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160117175744/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000623006/article/mike-mularkey-sheds-interim-tag-named-titans-coach|archivedate=January 17, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[New York Giants]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Tom Coughlin]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[Ben McAdoo]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |Resigned\n|Coughlin compiled a record of 102\u201390 ({{winning percentage|102|90}}) in 12 years with the Giants, a tenure that included three division titles, five playoff appearances (with a collective record of 8\u20133 in those games), and two Super Bowl wins ([[Super Bowl XLII]] and [[Super Bowl XLVI]], both over the [[New England Patriots]]). Since winning Super Bowl XLVI, the Giants had missed the playoffs every year and had accrued three consecutive losing seasons immediately prior to Coughlin's resignation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tom Coughlin says he's stepping down as Giants coach|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000617073/article/giants-will-not-retain-tom-coughlin-as-head-coach|website=NFL.com|date=January 4, 2016|accessdate=January 4, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160104213709/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000617073/article/giants-will-not-retain-tom-coughlin-as-head-coach|archivedate=January 4, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On January 14, McAdoo was promoted to head coach after serving as offensive coordinator with the team since 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hanzus|first=Dan|title=New York Giants hire Ben McAdoo as head coach|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000622234/article/new-york-giants-hire-ben-mcadoo-as-head-coach|website=NFL.com|date=January 14, 2016|accessdate=January 14, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160116225035/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000622234/article/new-york-giants-hire-ben-mcadoo-as-head-coach|archivedate=January 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|}\n\n====In-season====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:12%;\"| Team\n! style=\"width:10%;\"| 2016 head coach\n! style=\"width:8%;\"| Reason for leaving\n! style=\"width:8%;\"| Interim replacement\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Los Angeles Rams]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Jeff Fisher]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |Fired\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[John Fassel]]\n|After receiving a two-year contract extension prior to the season, Fisher was fired after going 4\u20139 in the season, and 31\u201345\u20131 (.414) in his tenure in St. Louis and Los Angeles. Under his tenure, the Rams never finished better than 7\u20138\u20131 ([[2012 St. Louis Rams season|2012]]) and never reached the playoffs.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mortensen|first1=Chris|title=Jeff Fisher fired as coach of Los Angeles Rams|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/18263718/jeff-fisher-fired-coach-st-louis-rams|website=espn.go.com|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=12 December 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20161216210341/http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/18263718/jeff-fisher-fired-coach-st-louis-rams|archivedate=December 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Fassel, the son of former NFL head coach [[Jim Fassel]], has been the Rams' special teams coach since 2012.\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Jacksonville Jaguars]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Gus Bradley]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Doug Marrone]]\n|Bradley was fired after four seasons and a 14\u201348 (.226) record with no playoff appearances.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rosenthal|first1=Gregg|title=Gus Bradley fired by Jacksonville Jaguars|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000759029/article/coach-gus-bradley-fired-by-jacksonville-jaguars|website=NFL.com|accessdate=18 December 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161218231429/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000759029/article/coach-gus-bradley-fired-by-jacksonville-jaguars|archivedate=December 18, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Marrone, the Jaguars' offensive line coach, was previously head coach of the [[Buffalo Bills]] from 2013\u201314.<ref>[http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2016/12/19/jaguars-name-marrone-interim-head-coach/ Jaguars name Marrone interim head coach] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20170524213227/http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2016/12/19/jaguars-name-marrone-interim-head-coach/ |date=May 24, 2017 }}.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Buffalo Bills]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Rex Ryan]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Anthony Lynn]]\n|Ryan was fired after two seasons and a 15\u201316 record with no playoff appearances. His twin brother, assistant head coach [[Rob Ryan]], also was dismissed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2016/12/27/bills-fire-rex-ryan/|title=Bills fire Rex Ryan|date=December 27, 2016|website=nbcsports.com|accessdate=May 2, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20170114200402/http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2016/12/27/bills-fire-rex-ryan/|archivedate=January 14, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Lynn began the 2016 season as running backs coach, then moved up to offensive coordinator when [[Greg Roman]] was fired in week 3, then interim head coach after Ryan's dismissal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000703603/article/buffalo-bills-fire-offensive-coordinator-greg-roman|title=Buffalo Bills fire offensive coordinator Greg Roman|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170102174738/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000703603/article/buffalo-bills-fire-offensive-coordinator-greg-roman|archivedate=January 2, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Front office===\n\n====Offseason====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Team\n!Position\n!2015 office holder\n!2015 interim\n!2016 replacement\n!Reason for leaving\n!Notes\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Cleveland Browns]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[General manager (American football)|GM]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Ray Farmer]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Sashi Brown]]\n| rowspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |Fired\n|The Browns released Ray Farmer after the final game of the 2015 regular season. He had been with the team for three seasons, two as general manager.<ref name=\"Brownsfired\"/>\n\nAs of April 2016, the Browns had not named a general manager; the duties are being filled in the interim by executive vice president of football operations Sashi Brown, an attorney by trade who has served in the Browns front office since 2013.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\" |[[Detroit Lions]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[General manager (American football)|GM]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Martin Mayhew]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Sheldon White]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Bob Quinn (American football)|Bob Quinn]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"|After starting the season 1\u20136, the Lions fired offensive coordinator Joe Lombardi. One week later, after another loss to the Kansas City Chiefs, owner Martha Firestone Ford fired Mayhew and Lewand.<ref>{{cite web|last=Orr|first=Conor|title=Lions fire GM Martin Mayhew, president Tom Lewand|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000573477/article/lions-fire-gm-martin-mayhew-president-tom-lewand|website=NFL.com|accessdate=2015-12-29|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106164706/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000573477/article/lions-fire-gm-martin-mayhew-president-tom-lewand|archivedate=January 6, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\nOn January 8, the Lions hired Quinn as their GM. Quinn had spent the previous 16 seasons in various positions in the front office of the [[New England Patriots]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Ortega|first=Mark E.|title=Detroit Lions hire Bob Quinn as general manager|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000619585/article/detroit-lions-hire-bob-quinn-as-general-manager|website=NFL.com|accessdate=13 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112025006/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000619585/article/detroit-lions-hire-bob-quinn-as-general-manager|archivedate=January 12, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\" \n||Team President\n||[[Tom Lewand]]\n| colspan=\"2\"|Rod Wood\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Miami Dolphins]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[General manager (American football)|GM]]\n| colspan=2 style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Dennis Hickey (American football)|Dennis Hickey]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Chris Grier \n| The Dolphins fired GM Hickey, who had spent the past two years with the team.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bergman|first=Jeremy|title=Miami Dolphins part ways with GM Dennis Hickey|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000613743/article/dolphins-part-ways-with-gm-dennis-hickey|website=NFL.com|accessdate=2 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130031014/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000613743/article/dolphins-part-ways-with-gm-dennis-hickey|archivedate=January 30, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Grier, Dolphins' director of college scouting, appointed as the new GM on January 5, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hanzus|first=Dan|title=Chris Grier named general manager of Dolphins|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000616944/article/chris-grier-named-general-manager-of-dolphins|website=NFL.com|accessdate=5 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105225032/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000616944/article/chris-grier-named-general-manager-of-dolphins|archivedate=January 5, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=2 style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Philadelphia Eagles]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|VP- Player Personnel\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|Ed Marynowitz\n| colspan=2 style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Tom Donahoe]]\n|Vice President of Player Personnel Ed Marynowitz was fired alongside head coach Chip Kelly on December 29, 2015. Donahoe last served as president and general manager of the [[Buffalo Bills]] from 2001 to 2005 but has largely been out of football in the ten years since his firing from that position.<ref name=\"Eaglesfired\"/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[General manager (American football)|GM]] (''de facto'')\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Chip Kelly]]\n| colspan=2 style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Howie Roseman]]\n|Roseman, who carried the title of \"[[director of football|executive vice president of football operations]]\" while Kelly handled general manager duties in 2015, reverted to his previous general manager duties after Kelly's firing.<ref name=\"Eaglesfired\"/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Tennessee Titans]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[General manager (American football)|GM]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Ruston Webster]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Jon Robinson (American football)|Jon Robinson]]\n|The Titans released Webster the Monday following their final game of the 2015 regular season. Webster had spent the past four seasons with the team.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sessler|first1=Marc|title=Titans parting ways with GM Ruston Webster|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000616975/article/titans-parting-ways-with-gm-ruston-webster|website=NFL.com|accessdate=2016-01-04|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160104191219/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000616975/article/titans-parting-ways-with-gm-ruston-webster|archivedate=January 4, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn January 14, the Titans hired Robinson as GM. Robinson had spent the previous three seasons as Director of Player Personnel for the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Patra|first=Kevin|title=Titans select Jon Robinson as new general manager|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000622397/article/titans-select-jon-robinson-as-new-general-manager|website=NFL.com|accessdate=14 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160116193406/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000622397/article/titans-select-jon-robinson-as-new-general-manager|archivedate=January 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Stadiums==\n\n===Atlanta Falcons===\nThe [[2016 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]] played their 25th and final season at the [[Georgia Dome]], with the team's new home field, [[Mercedes-Benz Stadium]], slated to open in {{nfly|2017}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mercedesbenzstadium.com/stadium-info/timeline/|title=Mercedes-Benz Stadium Timeline|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151226035552/http://mercedesbenzstadium.com/stadium-info/timeline/|archivedate=December 26, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Minnesota Vikings===\nThe [[2016 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]] played their first season at [[U.S. Bank Stadium]] in downtown [[Minneapolis]]. Construction on the team's new home field in downtown Minneapolis wrapped up at the start of the 2016 season. The new stadium is built on the site of the Vikings' former home, the [[Hubert H. Humphrey Metrodome]], which was demolished after the {{nfly|2013}} season.<ref name=\"Vikings stadium construction entering critical phase, transitioning for fall, winter\" >{{cite news|last=Olson|first=Rochelle|title=Vikings stadium construction entering critical phase, transitioning for fall, winter|url=http://www.startribune.com/vikings-stadium-construction-entering-critical-phase-transitioning-for-fall-winter/317670111/|accessdate=September 22, 2015|work=[[Star Tribune]]|publisher=Star Tribune Media Company, LLC.|date=July 21, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150725121643/http://www.startribune.com/vikings-stadium-construction-entering-critical-phase-transitioning-for-fall-winter/317670111/|archivedate=July 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Relocation of the Rams from St. Louis to Los Angeles===\n{{main|History of the National Football League in Los Angeles}}\nThe league scheduled a vote on whether to relocate one or two of its existing franchises to the [[Los Angeles metropolitan area]] on January 12, 2016. The league set a relocation fee of $550&nbsp;million for any team who is approved to relocate.<ref>{{cite web|last=Patra|first=Kevin|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000613870/article/los-angeles-relocation-fee-to-be-550-million-per-team|title=Los Angeles relocation fee to be $550 million per team|work=NFL.com|date=January 16, 2016|accessdate=January 3, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106004147/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000613870/article/los-angeles-relocation-fee-to-be-550-million-per-team|archivedate=January 6, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On January 4, three teams filed to relocate to Los Angeles: the [[Oakland Raiders]], [[San Diego Chargers]], and the [[St. Louis Rams]], all three of which had previously resided in the city at various points in their history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000617813/article/rams-chargers-raiders-apply-for-la-relocation|title=Rams, Chargers, Raiders apply for L.A. relocation|work=NFL.com|date=January 5, 2016|accessdate=January 5, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105072112/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000617813/article/rams-chargers-raiders-apply-for-la-relocation|archivedate=January 5, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Despite the Committee on Los Angeles Opportunities recommending the Raiders' and Chargers' joint proposal for a [[Carson Stadium|stadium in Carson, California]], on January 12, the league approved the Rams' proposal to relocate to [[Inglewood, California|Inglewood]] after three ballots, also giving the Chargers the option to share the Rams' stadium if they so choose. In the first two rounds of voting, Inglewood led Carson 21\u201311 and 20\u201312 respectively; by the third ballot, the Rams proposal had received effectively unanimous support from the other owners, with the final vote reaching 30\u20132 (the Raiders and Chargers themselves casting the lone opposing votes).<ref>{{cite web|last=Breer|first=Albert|title=Rams approved to relocate to Los Angeles|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000621645/article/expectation-is-owners-to-award-rams-inglewood-site?campaign=fb-nf-sf18682475-sf18682475|publisher=National Football League|date=January 12, 2016|accessdate=January 12, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160116091542/http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000621645/article/expectation-is-owners-to-award-rams-inglewood-site?campaign=fb-nf-sf18682475-sf18682475|archivedate=January 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  The [[2016 Los Angeles Rams season|Rams]] will play the first four seasons at the [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]], while their [[SoFi Stadium|new stadium]] is being built in Inglewood. The Rams previously played at the Coliseum during their first stint in Los Angeles from 1946 to 1979.\n\n====Rams bid for Los Angeles====\n{{main|SoFi Stadium}}\nThe Rams and the St. Louis CVC (Convention & Visitors Commission) began negotiating deals to get the Rams' home stadium, [[The Dome at America's Center]] (then known as Edward Jones Dome), into the top 25 percent of stadiums in the league (i.e., top eight teams of the thirty-two NFL teams in reference to luxury boxes, amenities and overall fan experience). Under the terms of the lease agreement, the St. Louis CVC was required to make modifications to the Edward Jones Dome in 2005. However, then-owner, [[Georgia Frontiere]], waived the provision in exchange for cash that served as a penalty for the city's noncompliance. The City of St. Louis, in subsequent years, made changes to the score board and increased the natural lighting by replacing panels with windows, although the overall feel remains dark. The minor renovations which totaled about $70&nbsp;million did not bring the stadium within the specifications required under the lease agreement.\n\nOn February 1, 2013, a three-person [[arbitral tribunal]] selected to preside over the arbitration process found that the Edward Jones Dome was not in the top 25% of all NFL venues as required under the terms of the lease agreement between the Rams and the CVC. The tribunal further found that the estimated $700&nbsp;million in proposed renovations by the Rams was not unreasonable given the terms of the lease agreement. Finally, the city of St. Louis was ordered to pay the Rams attorneys' fees which totaled a reported $2&nbsp;million.\n\nPublicly, city, county and state officials expressed no interest in providing further funding to the Edward Jones Dome in light of those entities, as well as taxpayers, continuing to owe approximately $300&nbsp;million more on that facility. As such, if a resolution could not reached by the end of the 2014\u20132015 NFL season and the City of St. Louis remains non-compliant in its obligations under the lease agreement, the Rams would be free to nullify their lease and relocate.\n\nOn January 31, 2014, both the ''Los Angeles Times'' and the ''St. Louis Post-Dispatch'' reported that Rams owner [[Stan Kroenke]] purchased 60 acres of land adjacent to the [[The Forum (Inglewood, California)|Forum]] in [[Inglewood, California]]. It would be, by the most conservative estimates, sufficient land on which an NFL-sized stadium may be constructed. The purchase price was rumored to have been between US$90\u2013100&nbsp;million. Commissioner Roger Goodell represented that Kroenke informed the league of the purchase. As an NFL owner, any purchase of land in which a potential stadium could be built must be disclosed to the league. This development further fueled rumors that the Rams intended to return its management and football operations to Southern California. The land was initially targeted for a Walmart Supercenter but [[Walmart]] could not get the necessary permits to build the center. Kroenke is married to [[Ann Walton Kroenke]] who is a member of the [[Walton family]] and many of Kroenke's real estate deals have involved Walmart properties.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wagoner|first=Nick|title=Stan Kroenke buys 60 acres in L.A.|url=http://espn.go.com/los-angeles/nfl/story/_/id/10380150/st-louis-rams-owner-stan-kroenke-buys-60-acres-land-los-angeles|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=September 4, 2014|date=February 1, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140921005816/http://espn.go.com/los-angeles/nfl/story/_/id/10380150/st-louis-rams-owner-stan-kroenke-buys-60-acres-land-los-angeles|archivedate=September 21, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ksdk.com/story/sports/nfl/rams/2014/01/30/stan-kroenke-plot-of-land-california-st-louis-rams/5069985/ |title=Report: Rams owner bought 60 acres of land in California |last=Piper |first=Brandie |publisher=Gannett Satellite Information Network, Inc. |date=January 31, 2014 |website=ksdk.com |accessdate=September 4, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140221154310/http://www.ksdk.com/story/sports/nfl/rams/2014/01/30/stan-kroenke-plot-of-land-california-st-louis-rams/5069985/ |archivedate=February 21, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Farmer|first1=Sam|last2=Vincent|first2=Roger|title=Owner of St. Louis Rams plans to build NFL stadium in Inglewood|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/nfl/la-sp-0105-nfl-la-stadium-20150105-story.html#page=1|accessdate=May 19, 2015|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=January 5, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528184109/http://www.latimes.com/sports/nfl/la-sp-0105-nfl-la-stadium-20150105-story.html#page=1|archivedate=May 28, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On January 5, 2015, The Los Angeles Times reported that [[Kroenke Sports & Entertainment]] and [[Stockbridge Capital Group]] were partnering up into developing a new NFL stadium on property owned by Kroenke. The project will include a stadium of up to 80,000 seats and a performance venue of 6,000 seats while reconfiguring the previously approved Hollywood Park plan for up to 890,000 square feet of retail, 780,000 square feet of office space, 2,500 new residential units, a 300-room hotel and 25 acres of public parks, playgrounds, open space and pedestrian and bicycle access. In lieu of this the city of St. Louis responded on January 9, 2015, by unveiling an [[National Car Rental Field|outdoor, open air, riverfront stadium]] that could have accommodated the Rams and an [[MLS]] team with the hope that the NFL bylaws can force them to stay. On February 24, 2015, the Inglewood City Council approved the stadium and the initiative with construction on the stadium planned to begin in December 2015. On December 21, 2015, Construction was officially underway at the Hollywood Park site for the stadium. On January 4, 2016, after St. Louis finished last in per-game attendance for the 2015 season,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fink|first1=James|last2=Thomas|first2=Scott|title=Buffalo Bills rank in upper half of NFL in attendance|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/buffalo/blog/morning_roundup/2016/01/buffalo-bills-rank-in-upper-half-of-nfl-in.html?ana=twt|accessdate=April 12, 2016|work=Buffalo Business First|publisher=[[Advance Publications]]|date=January 5, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170917213932/https://www.bizjournals.com/buffalo/blog/morning_roundup/2016/01/buffalo-bills-rank-in-upper-half-of-nfl-in.html?ana=twt|archivedate=September 17, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> the team filed a relocation application to relocate to Los Angeles and informed the NFL about this and released a statement on their website.\n\nOn January 12, 2016, the NFL owners approved the [[SoFi Stadium|Inglewood proposal]] and the Rams' relocation by a 30\u20132 vote; the Rams relocated almost immediately thereafter.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rams headed back to Los Angeles; Chargers have option to join|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/14558668/st-louis-rams-relocate-los-angeles|accessdate=January 13, 2016|work=ESPN News Services|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=January 13, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807231536/http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/14558668/st-louis-rams-relocate-los-angeles|archivedate=August 7, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Raiders and Chargers failed stadium bid====\n{{main|Carson Stadium}}\nOn February 19, 2015, the [[Oakland Raiders]] and [[San Diego Chargers]] announced plans for a privately financed $1.7 billion [[Carson Stadium|stadium]] that the two teams would build in [[Carson, California]] if they were to move to the Los Angeles market.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/12351492/san-diego-chargers-oakland-raiders-joint-stadium-plan-los-angeles |title=San Diego Chargers, Oakland Raiders have joint stadium plan near Los Angeles |website=Espn.go.com |date=2015-02-20 |accessdate=2015-12-02 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208115743/http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/12351492/san-diego-chargers-oakland-raiders-joint-stadium-plan-los-angeles |archivedate=December 8, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Such a move would have marked a return to the nation's second-largest market for both teams; the Raiders played in Los Angeles from 1982 to 1994 while the Chargers called LA home for their inaugural season in the [[American Football League]]. The Chargers were the only NFL team to play in [[Southern California]] at the time (until the Rams moved to Los Angeles in 2016), with [[San Diego]] being a {{convert|125|mi|km|adj=on}} distance from Los Angeles, and the Chargers counted Los Angeles as a secondary market. The Chargers have been looking to replace [[Qualcomm Stadium]] (which, like the Oakland Coliseum opened in the late 1960s) since [[San Diego Chargers stadium proposals|at least 2003]], and have had an annual out clause in which it can move in exchange for paying a fine to the city of San Diego for its remaining years on its lease. The Raiders, meanwhile, have been operating on year-to-year leases with [[Oakland Coliseum]], the stadium it has shared with the [[Oakland Athletics]] for most of its time in [[Oakland, California]], since the last long-term lease on that stadium ended in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/11229559/roger-goodell-floats-san-francisco-49ers-levi-stadium-oakland-raiders-option|title=Roger Goodell floats San Francisco 49ers' Levi's Stadium as Oakland Raiders option|website=Espn.go.com|date=2014-07-17|accessdate=2015-12-02|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119172029/http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/11229559/roger-goodell-floats-san-francisco-49ers-levi-stadium-oakland-raiders-option|archivedate=November 19, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nDue to both television contracts and NFL bylaws, had both of the [[Chargers\u2013Raiders rivalry|longstanding division rivals]] moved to LA, one of the teams would have been required to move to the [[NFC West]], something that Mark Davis volunteered the Raiders to be willing to do. The Raiders moving to the National Football Conference would have been considered ironic seeing that Davis's father [[Al Davis]] was a staunch opponent of the NFL during its rivalry and eventual [[AFL\u2013NFL merger|merger]] with the AFL. If such a scenario happened, a current NFC West team would have taken their spot in the [[AFC West]]. The early rumor was that the [[Seattle Seahawks]], who played in the AFC West from 1977 to 2001, would have been the favorite to have switched conferences with the Raiders. However, that team's [[49ers\u2013Seahawks rivalry|growing rivalry]] with the [[San Francisco 49ers]] had pointed to either the [[Arizona Cardinals]] or the then-[[St. Louis Rams]] switching conferences to take the Raiders' spot in the AFC West. Had the Rams stayed in St. Louis, switching them to the AFC would have allowed for a yearly home-and-home with the cross-state [[Kansas City Chiefs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/02/20/if-chargers-and-raiders-share-stadium-one-would-likely-move-to-nfc/|title=If Chargers and Raiders share stadium, one would likely move to NFC|last=Florio|first=Mike|publisher=NBC Sports|date=February 20, 2015|website=nbcsports.com|accessdate=April 30, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150425073539/http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/02/20/if-chargers-and-raiders-share-stadium-one-would-likely-move-to-nfc/|archivedate=April 25, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> As a portion of the Rams' 2016 schedule was already set because of their International Series appearance, the league could not realign until at least 2017.\n\nOn October 23, 2015, Mark Fabiani, Chargers spokesperson confirmed that the team planned to officially notify the NFL about its intentions to relocate to Los Angeles in January during the timetable when teams can request to relocate.<ref>{{cite news|last=Garrick|first=David|title=Chargers plan to file L.A. relocation papers|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/2015/oct/23/chargers-stadium-fabiani-relocation-los-angeles/|accessdate=November 29, 2015|work=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|date=October 23, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208083739/http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/2015/oct/23/chargers-stadium-fabiani-relocation-los-angeles/|archivedate=December 8, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\nOn January 4, 2016, both teams filed relocation applications for relocation to Los Angeles. On January 12, 2016, the NFL voted to allow the Rams move to Los Angeles and the Inglewood proposal, effectively rejecting and killing the Carson proposal. The Chargers were then given the option to join the Rams in Inglewood in 2016, with the Raiders having the option in 2017 if the Chargers declined; the Chargers announced on January 29 that they would remain in San Diego for the 2016 season as negotiations continued, but that if negotiations ultimately failed, they had reached an agreement in principle with the Rams to join them in Los Angeles once the Inglewood stadium is complete.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hirsh|first=Lou|title=Chargers to Play in S.D. for 2016; More Negotiations Planned|url=http://sdbj.com/news/2016/jan/29/chargers-play-sd-2016-more-negotiations-planned/|accessdate=January 29, 2016|work=[[San Diego Business Journal]]|date=January 29, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131062441/http://sdbj.com/news/2016/jan/29/chargers-play-sd-2016-more-negotiations-planned/|archivedate=January 31, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The Raiders reached an agreement on another one-year lease extension with Oakland Coliseum on February 11, 2016, keeping the team in Oakland for one more season.\n\nThe Raiders, having previously explored [[San Antonio, Texas]] as a potential relocation site in 2014, moved on to other potential relocation sites after the rejection of the Carson proposal, focusing on a stadium plan in the vicinity of [[Las Vegas, Nevada]]. On August 25, 2016, the Raiders applied for a trademark for the \"Las Vegas Raiders\" and unveiled artist renditions of the proposed Las Vegas stadium, given the tentative title \"[[Allegiant Stadium|Raiders Stadium]].\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Perez|first=A.J.|title=Oakland Raiders file to trademark 'Las Vegas Raiders' name|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/raiders/2016/08/25/raiders-las-vegas-trademark-relocation/89341228/|accessdate=August 25, 2016|work=[[USA Today]]|date=August 25, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827021927/http://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/raiders/2016/08/25/raiders-las-vegas-trademark-relocation/89341228/|archivedate=August 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Naming rights agreements===\n\n====Buffalo Bills====\nOn August 13, the [[Buffalo Bills]] and [[Pegula Sports and Entertainment]] reached an agreement to sell the naming rights to [[New Era Field|their stadium]] to the locally based [[New Era Cap Company]], a major headwear supplier to all of the major North American sports leagues. The stadium had previously been known as Rich Stadium from its opening in 1973, then as Ralph Wilson Stadium since 1998. The sale of naming rights came as somewhat of a surprise, as previous owner [[Ralph Wilson]] was firmly against selling the naming rights to the stadium and there were few companies in Western New York believed to have the money to pay the naming rights fee for an NFL stadium.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wawrow|first=John|title=Bills reach deal to sell stadium naming rights to New Era|url=http://pro32.ap.org/article/bills-reach-deal-sell-stadium-naming-rights-new-era|accessdate=August 13, 2016|agency=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=AP Sports|date=August 13, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815163025/http://pro32.ap.org/article/bills-reach-deal-sell-stadium-naming-rights-new-era|archivedate=August 15, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Miami Dolphins====\nCanadian-based [[financial services]] company [[Sun Life Financial]] had held the [[naming rights]] to the [[Miami Dolphins]]' stadium since {{nfly|2010}}, a deal which expired in the offseason. The team already announced that it was not going to renew the license.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jackson|first=Barry|title=Heat adds center; Dolphins Friday analysis, postscripts; New stadium name coming; Loria rejects overtures; Marlins issues; Heat|url=http://miamiherald.typepad.com/sports-buzz/2015/08/new-stadium-name-coming-loria-rejects-overtures-marlins-issues-heat.html|accessdate=August 15, 2015|work=[[Miami Herald]]|date=April 1, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150817080939/http://miamiherald.typepad.com/sports-buzz/2015/08/new-stadium-name-coming-loria-rejects-overtures-marlins-issues-heat.html|archivedate=August 17, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On August 16, 2016, it was reported that [[Hard Rock Cafe]] purchased the naming rights to the stadium, with the venue to be renamed [[Hard Rock Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Jackson|first=Barry|title=Miami Dolphins\u2019 stadium gets a new name: Hard Rock|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/nfl/miami-dolphins/article96001322.html|accessdate=August 16, 2016|work=[[Miami Herald]]|date=August 16, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817161447/http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/nfl/miami-dolphins/article96001322.html|archivedate=August 17, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Oakland Raiders====\nOn April 2, the O.co Coliseum, home of the [[Oakland Raiders]], reverted to its previous identity as the [[Oakland Alameda Coliseum]]. [[Online]] [[retailer]] [[Overstock.com]] held the [[naming rights]] to the Raiders' home field since {{nfly|2011}},<ref>{{cite web|last=Graf|first=Dan|title=O.co Coliseum is now just Oakland Coliseum again|url=http://www.foxsports.com/nfl/story/oakland-raiders-athletics-o-co-coliseum-naming-rights-040316|website=[[Foxsports.com]]|accessdate=April 3, 2016|date=April 3, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404051043/http://www.foxsports.com/nfl/story/oakland-raiders-athletics-o-co-coliseum-naming-rights-040316|archivedate=April 4, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> but opted out of the naming rights agreement, though it will continue to maintain its corporate sponsorship with the Athletics. The Raiders' home field has undergone numerous name changes in its history, including Network Associates Coliseum (1998\u20132004) and McAfee Coliseum (2004\u20132008).<ref>{{cite news|last=Johnson|first=Lizzie|title=O.co drops out; stadium is back to just Oakland Coliseum|url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/O-co-drops-out-stadium-is-back-to-just-Oakland-7224659.php|accessdate=April 2, 2016|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|date=April 2, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403033544/http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/O-co-drops-out-stadium-is-back-to-just-Oakland-7224659.php|archivedate=April 3, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Field surface changes===\n\n====Baltimore Ravens====\nOn December 2, 2015, the [[Baltimore Ravens]] announced a change in the surface at [[M&T Bank Stadium]] from their previous Shaw Sportexe Momentum 51 [[artificial turf]] to natural Bermuda grass for the first time since the 2001 season, by player preference for a natural surface.<ref>{{cite news|last=Zrebiec|first=Jeff|title=Ravens will switch to natural grass at M&T Bank Stadium in 2016|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/bal-ravens-switching-to-grass-field-20151204-story.html|accessdate=June 5, 2016|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|date=December 4, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160512193527/http://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/bal-ravens-switching-to-grass-field-20151204-story.html|archivedate=May 12, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The field was replaced beginning on February 4, 2016, timed to be installed by the start of the [[Johns Hopkins Blue Jays men's lacrosse|Johns Hopkins]] [[lacrosse]] season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gilbert|first=Pete|title=M&T Bank Stadium rips up turf for new grass field|url=http://www.wbaltv.com/sports/mt-bank-stadium-rips-up-turf-for-new-grass-field/37821266|accessdate=June 5, 2016|work=[[WBAL-TV]]|date=February 4, 2016|location=Baltimore|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160805040503/http://www.wbaltv.com/sports/mt-bank-stadium-rips-up-turf-for-new-grass-field/37821266|archivedate=August 5, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==New uniforms and patches==\n{{see also|NFL Color Rush}}\nAfter a trial run in 2015, the [[NFL Color Rush]] program returned for 2016 with all 32 NFL teams required to participate.<ref>{{cite web|title=Uni Watch: A colorful rush to judgment|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/17538646/uni-watch-goes-game-game-break-nfl-latest-color-rush-uniforms|accessdate=September 20, 2016|publisher=uniwatch.com|date=September 13, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917081248/http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/17538646/uni-watch-goes-game-game-break-nfl-latest-color-rush-uniforms|archivedate=September 17, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> To prevent issues with [[color blindness]] from the previous season, the NFL is scheduled match-ups and where color blindness would not be an issue. The Color Rush games were during the ''Thursday Night Football'' contests.<ref>{{cite web|last=Florio|first=Mike|authorlink=Mike Florio|title=NFL apparently has a plan to avoid color-blind confusion for Color Rush games|url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2016/04/16/nfl-apparently-has-a-plan-to-avoid-color-blind-confusion-for-color-rush-games/|website=[[Profootballtalk.com]]|publisher=[[NBC Sports]]|accessdate=August 13, 2016|date=April 16, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820232401/http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2016/04/16/nfl-apparently-has-a-plan-to-avoid-color-blind-confusion-for-color-rush-games/|archivedate=August 20, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n* The [[2016 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]] wore a patch to commemorate their 70th season.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fucillo|first=David|title=49ers to wear 70th anniversary patch, likely wear black jerseys again|url=http://www.ninersnation.com/2016/3/7/11177378/49ers-to-wear-70th-anniversary-patch-likely-wear-black-jerseys-again|website=ninersnation.com|publisher=[[SB Nation]]|accessdate=July 13, 2016|date=March 7, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818081110/http://www.ninersnation.com/2016/3/7/11177378/49ers-to-wear-70th-anniversary-patch-likely-wear-black-jerseys-again|archivedate=August 18, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* The [[2016 New Orleans Saints season|New Orleans Saints]] wore a patch to commemorate their 50th season.<ref>{{cite web|last=Delery|first=Wallace|title=Saints Unveil Addition To Their Uniform For 50th Anniversary Season|url=http://www.canalstreetchronicles.com/2016/3/19/11264174/saints-unveil-addition-to-their-uniform-for-50th-anniversary-season|website=canalstreetchronicles.com|publisher=[[SB Nation]]|accessdate=July 13, 2016|date=March 19, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160709073343/http://www.canalstreetchronicles.com/2016/3/19/11264174/saints-unveil-addition-to-their-uniform-for-50th-anniversary-season|archivedate=July 9, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* The [[2016 New York Giants season|New York Giants]] wore white pants instead of gray for their primary home jerseys.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kratch|first=James|title=Giants making uniform change for 2016 season|url=http://www.nj.com/giants/index.ssf/2016/07/giants_making_uniform_change_for_2016_season.html|accessdate=July 13, 2016|work=[[The Star-Ledger]]|date=July 11, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160712131239/http://www.nj.com/giants/index.ssf/2016/07/giants_making_uniform_change_for_2016_season.html|archivedate=July 12, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* The [[2016 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]] joined the handful of teams (such as the Cowboys and the Dolphins) that primarily wear their white jerseys at home. The change comes as a nod to the team's [[Fearsome Foursome (American football)|Fearsome Foursome era]] (they will play in the [[Los Angeles Coliseum|same stadium]] as those teams) and to accommodate the warmer climate of Los Angeles. The uniform itself will remain the same as it was in the last years in St. Louis.<ref>{{cite news|last=Klein|first=Gary|title=Rams will wear white uniforms for home games this season|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/rams/la-sp-rams-uniforms-20160811-snap-story.html|accessdate=August 12, 2016|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[tronc]]|date=August 11, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812003238/http://www.latimes.com/sports/rams/la-sp-rams-uniforms-20160811-snap-story.html|archivedate=August 12, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* The Miami Dolphins wore aqua for some of their home games in 2016 that include daytime.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dwork|first=David|title=Dolphins Unveil Uniforms For All Eight Home Games In 2016|url=http://miami.cbslocal.com/2016/05/23/dolphins-unveil-uniforms-for-all-eight-home-games-in-2016/|accessdate=October 18, 2016|work=[[WFOR-TV|CBS 4]]|date=May 23, 2016|location=Miami|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019145806/http://miami.cbslocal.com/2016/05/23/dolphins-unveil-uniforms-for-all-eight-home-games-in-2016/|archivedate=October 19, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* The [[2016 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]] retired their 1934 throwback uniforms after the 2016 season. The Steelers wore them for the last time on October 9, 2016 against the New York Jets.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wold|first=Rachel|title=Steelers to retire hideous \u2018bumblebee\u2019 throwback uniforms|url=http://sportsnaut.com/2016/08/steelers-to-retire-hideous-bumblebee-throwback-uniforms/|website=Sportsnaut.com|publisher=Sportsnaut|accessdate=October 18, 2016|date=August 3, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020035613/http://sportsnaut.com/2016/08/steelers-to-retire-hideous-bumblebee-throwback-uniforms/|archivedate=October 20, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* The [[2016 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]] wore 1966 throwback uniforms against the San Diego Chargers and San Francisco 49ers. The throwback uniforms are an altered version of the ones used from 2009\u20132012.<ref>{{cite web |last=Shaw |first=Morgan |url=http://www.atlantafalcons.com/news/blog/article-1/Falcons-to-Bring-Back-%E2%80%9966-Throwback-Uniforms/ecbd9946-0bd4-4387-8fd8-9dbe7ffa8c9f |title=Falcons to Bring Back \u201966 Throwback Uniforms |website=Atlantafalcons.com |date=2016-10-19 |accessdate=2016-12-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110193150/http://www.atlantafalcons.com/news/blog/article-1/Falcons-to-Bring-Back-%E2%80%9966-Throwback-Uniforms/ecbd9946-0bd4-4387-8fd8-9dbe7ffa8c9f |archivedate=January 10, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* The [[2016 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]] wore burgundy pants with their white jerseys<ref>{{cite news |last=Tesfatsion |first=Master |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/football-insider/wp/2016/09/30/redskins-players-and-fans-hope-the-burgundy-pants-are-here-to-stay/ |title=Redskins players, and fans, hope the burgundy pants are here to stay |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=2016-12-23 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203195447/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/football-insider/wp/2016/09/30/redskins-players-and-fans-hope-the-burgundy-pants-are-here-to-stay/ |archivedate=February 3, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and temporarily place gray facemasks on their helmets when wearing the 1937 throwback uniforms.\n\n==Media==\n\n===Broadcast rights===\nThis was the third season under broadcast contracts with [[ESPN Monday Night Football|ESPN]], [[NFL on CBS|CBS]], [[NFL on Fox|Fox]], and [[NFL on NBC|NBC]]. This includes \"cross-flexing\" (switching) Sunday afternoon games between CBS and Fox before or during the season (regardless of the conference of the visiting team). NBC will continue to air ''[[NBC Sunday Night Football|Sunday Night Football]]'', the annual [[National Football League Kickoff game|Kickoff game]], and the primetime Thanksgiving game. ESPN will continue airing ''[[Monday Night Football]]'' and the [[Pro Bowl]]. Fox will serve as the broadcaster of [[Super Bowl LI]].\n\n===Flexible scheduling===\nA change to the flexible scheduling rule takes effect for the 2016 season: in week 17, any game can be flexed into ''Sunday Night Football'', regardless of how many times a team had been featured on a primetime game that season. This change can, theoretically, allow a game with playoff implications in the final week of the season to be moved to primetime for greater prominence.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pelissero|first=Tom|title=NFL lifts prime-time flex scheduling restriction for Week 17|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2016/03/21/flex-scheduling-week-17/82090786/|accessdate=March 21, 2016|work=[[USA Today]]|date=March 21, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322100912/http://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2016/03/21/flex-scheduling-week-17/82090786/|archivedate=March 22, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> As in 2015, the NFL will continue the \"suspension\" of its [[blackout (broadcasting)|blackout]] policy, meaning that all games will be broadcast in their home markets regardless of ticket sales; Goodell stated that the league needed to continue investigating the impact of removing the blackout rules before such a change is made permanent.<ref>{{cite news|title=NFL continues suspension of local TV blackout policy for 2016|url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2016/03/28/nfl-continues-suspension-tv-blackout-rule|accessdate=March 29, 2016|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|date=March 28, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329092720/http://www.si.com/nfl/2016/03/28/nfl-continues-suspension-tv-blackout-rule|archivedate=March 29, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===''Thursday Night Football''===\nThe league's contract with CBS for ''[[Thursday Night Football]]'' expired after the 2015 season and was placed back up for bids.<ref name=\"sbj-tnf2016\">{{cite web|title=NFL Ready To Accept New Bids For Thursday Night Package, Including Streaming Companies|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/2015/12/16/Media/NFL-Thursday.aspx|website=Sports Business Journal|accessdate=16 December 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222112931/http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/2015/12/16/Media/NFL-Thursday.aspx|archivedate=December 22, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On February 1, 2016, the NFL announced that ''Thursday Night Football'' would be shared between CBS, NBC, and NFL Network for the 2016 season. CBS and NBC will each air five games, which will be simulcast by NFL Network, along with an additional eight games exclusively on NFL Network, the production of which will be split between the two networks. Commissioner Roger Goodell that the league was \"thrilled to add NBC to the ''Thursday Night Football'' mix, a trusted partner with a proven track record of success broadcasting NFL football in primetime, and look forward to expanding with a digital partner for what will be a unique tri-cast on broadcast, cable and digital platforms.\"<ref name=\"deadline-tnf2016nbccbs\">{{cite web|title=CBS & NBC To Share \u2018Thursday Night Football\u2019 With NFL Network; League Eyes \"Tri-Cast\" With Digital Partner|url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/thursday-night-football-cbs-nbc-share-nfl-network-1201694273/|website=Deadline.com|accessdate=1 February 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202032721/http://deadline.com/2016/02/thursday-night-football-cbs-nbc-share-nfl-network-1201694273/|archivedate=February 2, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On April 5, 2016, it was announced that [[Twitter]] had acquired non-exclusive worldwide digital streaming rights to the 10 broadcast television TNF games, including to mobile devices (this is the first time any NFL games have been made available to mobile devices not subscribed to [[Verizon Wireless]], whose NFL Mobile app holds exclusive rights to all other games). This partnership will also include content for Twitter's live streaming service [[Periscope (app)|Periscope]], such as behind-the-scenes access.<ref name=\"ars-tnftwitter\">{{cite web|last1=Brodkin|first1=Jon|title=Twitter buys NFL streaming rights for 10 Thursday Night Football games|url=https://arstechnica.com/business/2016/04/twitter-buys-nfl-streaming-rights-for-10-thursday-night-football-games/|website=Ars Technica|publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast|accessdate=5 April 2016|date=5 April 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405174814/http://arstechnica.com/business/2016/04/twitter-buys-nfl-streaming-rights-for-10-thursday-night-football-games/|archivedate=April 5, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Internet streaming for International Series===\nAfter 2015's Bills\u2013Jaguars International Series contest was a modest success, the league was initially expected to make all three of the 2016 London games exclusive to the Internet. [[Yahoo! Screen]], which carried the 2015 contest, shut down in January 2016;<ref>{{cite news|last=Thielman|first=Sam|title=Yahoo kills off Screen video service less than four years after launch|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/jan/04/yahoo-screen-video-service-ends|accessdate=April 7, 2016|work=[[The Guardian]]|location=New York City|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403071034/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/jan/04/yahoo-screen-video-service-ends|archivedate=April 3, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> the bidders on the three games (which may or may not go to the same broadcaster) included [[YouTube]] and [[Apple TV]], both of which bid on the 2015 game but were passed up in favor of Yahoo!'s bid.<ref>{{cite news|last=Toonkel|first=Jessica|title=Exclusive: NFL to live-stream all London games, in talks with Apple, Google|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-nfl-london-livestream-idUSKBN0UM1YJ20160108|accessdate=April 7, 2016|agency=[[Reuters]]|publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]]|date=January 8, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409160523/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-nfl-london-livestream-idUSKBN0UM1YJ20160108|archivedate=April 9, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Ultimately, the league decided not to make the International Series games Web-exclusive, instead focusing its efforts on the ''Thursday Night Football'' partnership with Twitter.<ref>{{cite news|last=Toonkel|first=Jessica|title=NFL decides against live stream of London games next season|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/nfl-decides-against-live-stream-145206760.html|accessdate=April 11, 2016|work=[[Yahoo! Finance]]|agency=[[Reuters]]|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|date=April 11, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413091940/http://finance.yahoo.com/news/nfl-decides-against-live-stream-145206760.html|archivedate=April 13, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Personnel changes===\n[[Mike Tirico]], the lead play-by-play announcer for ''Monday Night Football'', announced his departure from ESPN on May 9, 2016; he joins NBC, where he was originally designated to lead the network's broadcast team for ''Thursday Night Football'' telecasts. Replacing Tirico on ''MNF'' is [[Sean McDonough]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Mandell|first=Nick|title=ESPN confirms that Mike Tirico will leave network; will be replaced by Sean McDonough on MNF|url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2016/05/mike-tirico-espn|accessdate=May 9, 2016|work=[[USA Today]]|date=May 9, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160510102154/http://ftw.usatoday.com/2016/05/mike-tirico-espn|archivedate=May 10, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The move was initially reported in April but not confirmed until the next month.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ourand|first=John|title=Sources: ESPN Mainstay Mike Tirico Leaving To Join NBC|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Closing-Bell/2016/04/25/Tirico.aspx|publisher=Sports Business Daily|date=April 25, 2016|accessdate=April 25, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426195922/http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Closing-Bell/2016/04/25/Tirico.aspx|archivedate=April 26, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> However, shortly before the start of the regular season, the league exercised a clause in its television contract with NBC demanding that any broadcast team that calls ''Sunday Night Football'' also call ''Thursday Night Football'' as well, effectively forcing [[Al Michaels]] to call both packages unless he and Tirico also split Sundays (this was the scenario that was ultimately chosen; on most weeks when Michaels calls a Thursday game, Tirico will call Sundays).<ref>{{cite news|last=Raissman|first=Bob|title=Al Michaels, not Mike Tirico, will be calling NFL games on Thursday for NBC|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/football/al-michaels-not-mike-tirico-calling-thursday-nfl-games-article-1.2759020|accessdate=August 24, 2016|work=[[New York Daily News]]|date=August 20, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160823142852/http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/football/al-michaels-not-mike-tirico-calling-thursday-nfl-games-article-1.2759020|archivedate=August 23, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> This is also the final season [[Chris Berman]] serves as a studio analyst for ESPN's NFL programming; Berman has been with ESPN since the network's inception in 1979.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thebiglead.com/2016/05/26/chris-berman-retiring-espn-after/|last=McIntyre|first=Jason|title=Chris Berman's Contract Won't Be Renewed at ESPN, Who Replaces Him?|work=USA Today|date=May 26, 2016|accessdate=May 26, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160527230441/http://thebiglead.com/2016/05/26/chris-berman-retiring-espn-after/|archivedate=May 27, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\nThis would also end up being [[Phil Simms]]' last season as lead color commentator for the [[NFL on CBS]]. [[Tony Romo]], who would retire at the end of this season, would replace Simms as lead color commentator on CBS. Simms will join [[The NFL Today]] next season. This would also lead to [[Tony Gonzalez]] and [[Bart Scott]], leaving The NFL Today. Gonzalez will now be on [[Fox NFL Kickoff]]. Replacing Gonzalez and Scott will be Simms and [[Nate Burleson]], who comes over from [[NFL Network]]'s football morning talk show, [[Good Morning Football]], although he will remain with the show. This would also be the last season for [[Solomon Wilcots]] at [[NFL on CBS|CBS]]. [[James Lofton]] from [[NFL on Westwood One Sports|Westwood One]], will replace Wilcots next season. Meanwhile, at Fox, this would be the last season for [[John Lynch (American football)|John Lynch]], who would leave to be the next general manager of the [[San Francisco 49ers]]. Replacing Lynch next season, would be [[Charles Davis (defensive back)|Charles Davis]] who would move up from the #4 team at Fox to join Kevin Burkhardt at the end of this season.\n\n==Television viewers and ratings==\n\n===Most watched regular season games===\n*DH = doubleheader; SNF = [[NBC Sunday Night Football]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Rank || Date !! colspan=4|Matchup !! Network || Viewers (millions) || TV rating <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsmediawatch.com/nfl-tv-ratings-viewership-nbc-cbs-fox-espn-nfln-regular-season-playoffs/|title=The NFL Ratings Page|work=SportsMediaWatch.com|accessdate=September 29, 2016}}</ref> || Window || Significance\n|-\n| 1\n| November 24, 4:30 ET\n| [[2016 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]]\n| 26\n| '''[[2016 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]]'''\n| 31\n| rowspan=3|[[NFL on Fox|Fox]]\n| 35.1 \n| 14.5\n| [[NFL on Thanksgiving Day|Thanksgiving]]\n| [[Cowboys\u2013Redskins rivalry|Cowboys\u2013Redskins Rivalry]]\n|-\n| 2\n| November 13, 4:25 ET\n| '''[[2016 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]]'''\n| 35\n| [[2016 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]]\n| 30\n| 28.9\n| 16.4\n| Late DH{{Ref label|a|a|none}}\n| [[Cowboys\u2013Steelers rivalry|Cowboys\u2013Steelers Rivalry]]\n|-\n| 3\n| October 16, 4:25 ET\n| '''[[2016 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]]'''\n| 30\n| [[2016 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]]\n| 16\n| 28.0 \n| 15.8\n| Late DH{{Ref label|b|b|none}}\n| [[1967 NFL Championship Game|Ice Bowl]] Rematch\n|-\n| 4\n| November 24, 12:30 ET\n| [[2016 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]]\n| 13\n| '''[[2016 Detroit Lions season|Detroit Lions]]'''\n| 16\n||[[NFL on CBS|CBS]]\n| 27.6\n| 13.0\n| [[NFL on Thanksgiving Day|Thanksgiving]]\n| [[Lions\u2013Vikings rivalry|Lions\u2013Vikings Rivalry]]\n|- \n| 5\n| September 11, 4:25 ET\n| '''[[2016 New York Giants season|New York Giants]]''' \n| 20\n| [[2016 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]]\n| 19\n| [[NFL on Fox|Fox]]\n| 27.5\n| 15.5\n| Late DH{{Ref label|c|c|none}}\n| [[Cowboys\u2013Giants rivalry|Cowboys\u2013Giants 